trivia: Sonja's luxury item was a ukelele.
Sonja and Stacey Stillman are the first contestants from California.
Sonja is the first lesbian Survivor contestant.
Sonja was the oldest female contestant on Borneo, and also the oldest female contestant in Survivor history.
Sonja and B.B. Andersen are the only castaways to be born in the 1930s.

Sonja is the first ever Survivor contestant to be voted out.
She also is the first Survivor contestant that received a vote against them (from Susan Hawk).
Sonja won $2,500 for her time on Borneo.
Sonja is the oldest woman to be the first person voted out of a season and is tied with Jim Lynch for being the oldest first boot of the season.
Sonja is one of two women over the age of 60 years old to play Survivor. The other is Gillian Larson from Survivor: Gabon.
He was the oldest member of the Pagong tribe.
B.B. was the first contestant from Kansas.
B.B. was the first contestant to be featured in the opening credits.
B.B. was the first male contestant to be voted off Survivor.
B.B.'s luxury item was a towel.
Stacey and Sonja Christopher are the first Survivor contestants from California.

When Stacey was voted out, her torch was already extinguished because of the pouring rain. After she left Tribal Council, the remaining Tagi members were advised to stay at Tribal Council until the rain subsides the next day.
With her lawsuit, it was revealed that Survivor contestants must sign a gag order that forbids them to spoil the possible outcome of their season, or face a $5,000,000 penalty.
Stacey's luxury item was a camera.
Ramona's luxury item was a journal.
Ramona and Gervase Peterson are the first contestants from the state of New Jersey as well as the first African-American contestants.
Ramona was the first castaway to sit out of a challenge.
Ramona was the only female to be voted out of Pagong.

In a SurvivorOz interview, Ramona revealed her least favorite season was Survivor: Africa because it was hard for her to watch the castaways suffer from dehydration, while her favorite was Survivor: Marquesas because of Vecepia Towery, who played what Ramona believed was a straight up game.
Dirk's luxury item was a bible.
Along with Susan Hawk, Dirk was the first contestant from Wisconsin.
Dirk was the youngest male contestant in Borneo.
Dirk is the first Survivor contestant whose elimination was caused by an alliance.
Dirk was the only male to be voted out of Tagi.
Dirk was the first contestant to ever be blindsided.
Joel's luxury item was a bottle of shampoo.
Joel is the first contestant from Arkansas.
Starting with Joel, all the remaining members of Pagong were voted out in succession.
Gretchen's luxury item was a toothbrush.
Gretchen was the first contestant from Tennessee.
Gretchen was the oldest female member of Pagong.
Gretchen was the first contestant to be voted out of a merged tribe.
Gretchen is the first contestant to be voted out first after the merge and not be a part of the jury.
Gretchen was the first contestant to be voted out by a plurality, being voted out with less than half of the total counted votes.
At the Reunion Show, her last name was mistakenly listed as Klug, which was the last name of her fellow Pagong tribemate, Joel.
Greg's luxury item was a frisbee.
Greg was the first contestant from Colorado.
Greg was the youngest male on Pagong.
Greg was the first Survivor contestant to become a member of the jury.
Greg was the first person to win a Loved Ones Challenge.
Greg was the first person to win individual immunity.
Greg was the only member of Pagong to vote for Richard Hatch at Final Tribal Council.

Jeff Probst stated that during the first Tribal Council that Pagong went to, Greg got on his nerves by mocking him and the rest of the crew. However, Greg later became one of Probst's favorite contestants.
Greg was nominated in Survivor: America's Tribal Council as the "Sexiest Male Contestant", but lost to Colby Donaldson.
Greg was asked several times to be on Survivor again but had to decline on the basis of career commitments.
Greg is the only contestant from Borneo to win individual immunity and never return for another season.

occupation: YMCA Basketball Coach; Cigar Lounge Owner

trivia: Colleen is the first contestant from Florida.
Colleen's luxury item was a bar of soap.
Colleen is the first female to wear the Buff as a skirt.
Colleen is the first castaway to cry during the show. This was for losing the Immunity Challenge and having to send somebody home.
Colleen is the first contestant to cast an ouster vote for the eventual winner of their season.

Colleen is the first female to win an individual challenge.
Colleen is the first contestant to be allowed to bring one tribemate with them on a reward.

Colleen was the last standing Pagong member, making her the first contestant to be the last one remaining from their original tribe. Thus, Colleen is the highest ranking castaway of Pagong and is the first castaway to be the highest ranking castaway from a starting tribe.
Colleen intended to vote for Richard Hatch in the Final Tribal Council, but he answered poorly to her question, thus switching her vote to Kelly Wiglesworth.

Colleen was asked to come back for Survivor: All-Stars, but she was the only one from Survivor: Borneo who declined, stating she "had moved on with her life" and "just genuinely didn't want to go through that again." Her replacement in All-Stars would end up being fellow Pagong tribemate Jenna Lewis. She was also considered for Survivor: Heroes vs. Villains, but ultimately declined.
Colleen was nominated in Survivor: America's Tribal Council for "Hottest Female", but lost to Amber Brkich.

Sean's luxury item was a razor.
He and Survivor: The Australian Outback contestant Kel Gleason (who also brought a razor) are the only male contestants to continuously shave their facial hair during their time on the show.
Sean is the first contestant from the state of New York.

Sean's alphabet strategy was referenced during a challenge in Survivor: All-Stars, where the castaways were to answer questions about the preceding seven seasons. This left All-Stars contestant Jenna Lewis smirking, being a victim of the strategy herself.
Despite his seemingly random way of voting, only three of his ten votes were in the minority.
Sean is one of the two non-immune players that were present at the Tribal Council in "The Merger" but didn't receive any votes against him. The other is Kelly Wiglesworth.
Sean was the first player to have his loved one visit the camp.
Sean is the first person to be voted out of a tribe unanimously.
Sean was the first contestant ever to enter the Tribal Council area.
Sean is the first Tagi member to be voted out of Rattana.
Sean was the only person from Tagi who made the merge that hasn't returned for a future season.
Sean was the only male member of Rattana who did not win individual immunity.
Debb was the oldest female member of Kucha.
Debb was the first Survivor castaway to compete on the show who was born in the 1950s.
Debb was the first woman to be unanimously voted out. She was also the first person to be unanimously voted out before the merge.
Kel's luxury item was a shaving kit.
Kel and Colby Donaldson are the first contestants from Texas.
Kel is the first Hispanic-American player to compete on Survivor.
Maralyn's luxury item was a lipstick.
For her audition tape, she videotaped herself spending 7 weeks living and sleeping inside a trash dumpster.
Maralyn was the oldest female contestant in The Australian Outback and the oldest member of Ogakor.
Maralyn is the only female member of Ogakor to not make the merge.
When Maralyn was voted off, she gave Amber Brkich her "Mad Dog" cap.
While in the Outback, Maralyn mistook fellow Ogakor tribe member Kel Gleason by calling him "Cal."
Maralyn is the only female member of Ogakor who did not appear on Survivor: All-Stars.
Maralyn, along with fellow The Australian Outback castaway Rodger Bingham, were the first Survivor castaways to compete on the show who were born in the 1940s.

Maralyn gave up smoking in order to be on Survivor. During her time in the Outback, a nicotine patch was visible on her arm on several occasions. Upon being voted out she stated in her final confessional that she had the urge to smoke a cigarette.
Maralyn was inspired to learn how to play the didgeridoo after being on Survivor: The Australian Outback. She even played the instrument at the Reunion Show.
Mitchell Olson is the tallest Survivor contestant, at 7 feet (213 cm). Scot Pollard and Cliff Robinson are just behind him, at 6' 11" (210 cm) and 6' 10" (208 cm) respectively.
Mitchell's luxury item was a song book.
Mitchell was the youngest male on Ogakor.
Mitchell became the first castaway to be eliminated over a deadlock tie vote and the first person to be voted out by counting their previous Tribal Council votes.
Mitchell Olson later wrote a song about his season called Back From the Outback. It was a parody of I Will Survive by Gloria Gaynor.
Nick's luxury item was a frisbee.
Nick was the youngest male contestant in The Australian Outback.
Nick is the first contestant from the state of Washington.
Nick was the first and only Kucha member to win individual immunity and the only Kucha to win an individual challenge in general.
Nick was the first contestant to purchase an item in a Survivor Auction, buying four Doritos and a cup of salsa for $60.
He was the oldest contestant on The Australian Outback.

Rodger is the first contestant from Kentucky.
His tribemates and Jeff Probst gave him the moniker "Kentucky Joe".
Rodger was the second contestant who had brought a bible as his luxury item, the first one being Dirk Been from the previous season.
Rodger, along with fellow The Australian Outback castaway Maralyn Hershey, were the first Survivor castaways to compete on the show who were born in the 1940s.

When Ogakor was speculating which castaway was evacuated in "Trial by Fire", several members of the tribe (Jerri Manthey in particular) believed that Rodger had a stroke. Needless to say, this was not the case.
He was shortlisted for Survivor: All-Stars and Survivor: Guatemala.
Elisabeth was the youngest member of Kucha.
Elisabeth's Luxury Item was a self-made headdress.
Elisabeth is the first contestant from the state of Massachusetts.

After the merge, Elisabeth voted against every member of Ogakor, with the exception of Tina Wesson, twice in a row (for Colby Donaldson in the same Tribal Council, then twice against Jerri Manthey, twice against Amber Brkich, and twice against Keith Famie). Furthermore, in the Final Tribal Council, she voted for Tina, the only Ogakor member of Barramundi that she did not vote against.

Elisabeth and Keith Famie were the only contestants in Survivor history who reached 39 days, but did not make it to the Final Tribal Council, since the season was three days longer than the previous season and subsequent seasons.
Elisabeth is the only contestant to be voted out on Day 39.
Elisabeth is the only contestant to make it to Day 39 and come in fourth place.
Elisabeth is the first person to become a member of the jury on Day 39. She would be followed by Laurel Johnson.
Elisabeth was asked to return for All-Stars, but declined due to her job offer as a co-host on The View. Elisabeth would be replaced by fellow The Australian Outback castaway Amber Brkich.
Elisabeth was nominated in Survivor: America's Tribal Council in the "Hottest Female Contestant" category, but lost to Amber Brkich.

Eventual Cook Islands castaway Rebecca Borman used to work as Elisabeth's make-up artist on ABC's The View. When Rebecca revealed to Elisabeth that she competed, Rebecca claimed that Elisabeth "was literally floored".
Elisabeth was considered to be a candidate for Cambodia, but declined.
Keith's luxury item was a pan he used to cook paella.
Keith and Michael Skupin are the first contestants from Michigan.
Keith is the oldest male on Ogakor.
Keith is the first chef to compete on Survivor.
Keith is the first male contestant to win two consecutive individual Immunity Challenges.

Keith holds the record for playing the most days among those who played only once - 41 days, since his season was the longest, lasting 42 days.
Keith is the only contestant to be voted off on Day 41.
Keith is one of two contestants (the other being Elisabeth Filarski) to reach Day 39 and not be one of the finalists.
Keith is the only male contestant to vote for Tina Wesson to become the Sole Survivor.
Of the five Ogakor members who made the merge, only Keith did not return for a future season.

During the Survivor: The Australian Outback Reunion Show, it was mentioned that Keith was originally slated for Survivor: Borneo.
Keith was originally slated for Borneo, but because all the spots were filled he got to compete on The Australian Outback.
Keith was adopted at a young age. His biological father was the legendary former Key West mayor, Captain Tony Tarracino.
Keith's recipe for his Paella was included on the Survivor: The Australian Outback DVD as a special feature, and included a step-by-step demonstration video done by Keith himself.
Diane's luxury item was a journal.
Diane is the first contestant from Nebraska.
Jessie's luxury item was her grandmother's necklace.

Jessie is the first castaway to be originally from Puerto Rico.
She is also the first castaway to be originally from a U.S. Territory.
Carl is the oldest member of Samburu and oldest male contestant on Survivor: Africa.
Carl's luxury item was a dental kit.
Carl is the only contestant to be eliminated via a nature quiz tiebreaker.
Linda's luxury item was a string necklace.
Linda was the oldest female member of the original Samburu tribe.
Silas was the youngest member of Samburu and the youngest male contestant in Survivor: Africa.
Despite his occupation being announced as "Germantown bartender" in the show, Silas said in an interview he never was a bartender in Germantown.
Silas's luxury item was his pillow.

Silas's nickname was Chip, apparently because of his amateur boxing career. Because his father used to be a boxer too, people said he was "a chip off the old block." When Frank Garrison voted against Silas at the fourth Tribal Council he wrote on his ballot "Silas a.k.a. Chip."
Silas is the first victim of a game twist. He was eliminated due to the first ever tribe switch.
Lindsey was the youngest female on Samburu.
Lindsey's luxury item was a beach ball.
Lindsey is the first contestant from Oregon.
Lindsey is the only castaway to be involved in a deadlock tie more than once.

Lindsey is the only person to date to attempt to leave the Tribal Council area and be ordered to sit back down by Jeff Probst. When the first vote ended in a 3-3 tie between her and Tom Buchanan, she got up to leave, assuming she was eliminated. Probst told her to sit back down and had the contestants vote again for either her or Tom. When the second vote was also deadlocked, Probst asked about previous votes and Lindsey had the most and thus was eliminated.
Lindsey was the third and final person to be eliminated because of previous votes.
Lindsey is the first person to be voted out while staying on her same tribe in a tribe switch.
Lindsey is tied with Clarence Black for most votes against her in Survivor: Africa with 12.
Lindsey is the first contestant to have received the most votes in the season and to have been voted-out pre-merge.
Clarence's luxury item was camouflage paint.
Clarence was the youngest male on the Boran tribe.
Clarence was the only contestant who stayed on Boran after the tribe switch who didn't make to the Final Tribal Council.
Clarence is the first male to get the most votes cast against them in a season, tying with Lindsey Richter in Survivor: Africa with 12.
Kelly is the first contestant to have the same first name as a previous contestant.
Kelly was the youngest contestant on Survivor: Africa.
Kelly's luxury items were crochet needles and yarn.
Following the show, Kelly was roommates with fellow Survivor: Africa contestant Kim Powers.
Starting with Kelly, every castaway who was on Samburu at some point was voted out until none were left. This included Lex and Big Tom, who were on Samburu post tribe switch.

Kelly never pierced any part of her body. This caused a lot of controversy during Final Four Immunity Challenge. The anomaly was the final question (Which female contestant has no piercings?) The official answer, given by Kim Johnson to earn the win, was Kelly Goldsmith. Lex van den Berghe answered the question with Lindsey Richter's name, who, unknown to the producers, also had no piercings.
Brandon's luxury item was lip balm.
Brandon is the first LGBT contestant to be on the jury.
Brandon was the first male to be the first male on the jury of a season and to not win individual immunity.
As revealed in the Fallen Comrades challenge on Day 37, Brandon has a tattoo of a black widow spider on his back.
Frank's luxury item was a pair of whitetail antlers.
Frank turned 43 on Day 12 of Survivor: Africa.
Frank is the highest placing male member of the original Samburu tribe.
Frank is the only person to vote against Kim Johnson.

Kim Powers and Kim Johnson, are the first contestants to compete in a season with the same first name.
They are also the second highest-ranking member of their original tribes.
Kim's luxury item was a string necklace.
Teresa's luxury item was a lucky bullet necklace.
According to Teresa, her fellow Samburu tribe mates called her "Tina" earlier in the game. In response to this, Teresa asked her tribemates to call her "T-Bird".
Teresa is the first out of many women to win the When It Rains, It Pours challenge.
Teresa was the first woman to win individual immunity since Kelly Wiglesworth won consecutive challenges in Borneo.
Teresa was the first woman to win the first individual Immunity Challenge of the season.
Teresa was the only Samburu member to win individual immunity.
Teresa was the last original former Samburu member standing.
Teresa was the first woman to finish in 5th place.
Teresa was the first woman to win individual immunity but not make it to the Final Tribal Council.
Teresa was considered for Survivor: All-Stars, but did not make the final cast.

Kim was the oldest contestant in Africa.
Kim is the first female to be the oldest contestant in a season.
Kim is the oldest contestant to win the Final Immunity Challenge, being 56 at the time of filming.
Kim is the first oldest contestant of a season to reach the Final Tribal Council and is one of five to do so.
Kim is the oldest person to make it to Day 39 and the Final Tribal Council by date of birth.
Kim Johnson and Kim Powers are the first pair of contestants with the same first name to compete in the same season.
Kim had the first confessional in Africa.
Kim's luxury item was paints and brush.
Kim is the second contestant to play an individual Immunity Challenge wearing the Immunity Necklace. The first was Gervase Peterson in the episode "Old and New Bonds".
Kim is the first finalist to receive fewer than three jury votes.
Kim is the only member of the Africa final four to not return for a future season.

Kim is the only contestant from Africa to have never been voted out at any point in her Survivor career.
Kim is the earliest appearing castaway to never been eliminated from Survivor.
Peter's luxury item was a bottle of cologne.
Peter was the oldest male on the Maraamu tribe.
Peter is the first male contestant to be the first person voted out of a season and the first male to finish in 16th place.
Peter's interview with Survivor Oz was voted the best for the 2013/14 at The Ozcars.
Patricia is the oldest female contestant on Marquesas.
Patricia's luxury item was a lock of Arabian hair.
Patricia is the first contestant from South Carolina.
Every time she attended Tribal Council, Patricia received a vote.
He was nominated in Survivor: America's Tribal Council in the "Sexiest Male" category, but lost to Colby Donaldson.
Hunter's luxury item was a pair of Navy Wings.
Sarah is the youngest member of the Maraamu tribe.
Sarah had the most votes cast against her in Marquesas, with 11.
Sarah's luxury item was a pillow.
Sarah is the first woman to be the first person voted out after a tribe swap.
Sarah received at least 2 votes at every Tribal Council she attended.
Gabe is the youngest male contestant on Marquesas.
Gabe's luxury item was his childhood teddy bear.
Gabe is the first contestant from North Carolina.
Gabe is the first player in Survivor to be the only person voted out from a tribe pre-merge; he was the only member of Rotu to not make the merge.
Gina was the last original Maraamu member to be voted out before the merge.
Gina's luxury item was an adventure bag.
Gina is the only original Maraamu member who won tribal immunity in the Maraamu tribe.
Gina is the highest placing castaway to never be a part of the Rotu tribe.
John's luxury item was a bottle of massage oils.
John is the first male castaway from Nebraska.
John is the first jury member to be given permission to speak at a Tribal Council that wasn't the Final Tribal Council.
Zoe's luxury item was a necklace.
Zoe is the first contestant from Maine.
Zoe is the only female member of Soliantu to not win individual immunity.
Zoe is the only member of the Rotu Four to vote for Neleh Dennis to win the season.
Tammy's luxury item was a picture of her fiancé and her pet dog.
Tammy is the first contestant from Arizona.

Robert's luxury item was a voodoo doll. He intended for the doll to represent the opposing tribe. Prior to the first Immunity Challenge, Robert and the other Rotu tribe members took turns sticking pins and needles into the doll. Ironically, Maraamu ended up losing all but three of the tribal challenges.
His nickname, The General, comes from one of his tattoos.

Robert was the only male to win an Individual Immunity Challenge during Marquesas.
Robert is the first male castaway who was the only man to win Individual Immunity during a season. This would not happen again until Survivor: Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers when Cole Medders replicated this feat.
Robert is the highest ranking castaway to not be a part of the Maraamu tribe. Everyone who outlasted Robert was a member of Maraamu at some point as a result of the switch.
Robert was the first male who was eliminated in sixth place.
Sean's luxury item was a bible.
Sean, Rob Mariano, and Vecepia Towery are the first contestants to be on a tribe with every castaway on their season. They are also the only ones to do so in a season with just two pre-merge tribes.
Sean is the only juror from the original Maraamu tribe in Marquesas.
Paschal is the oldest contestant on Marquesas.
Paschal's luxury item was an American flag.
Paschal had the first confessional in Marquesas.
Paschal was the first contestant to be the sole representative of their gender after a tribe switch.
Paschal and Neleh Dennis voted for the same person at every Tribal Council they attended.
Paschal is the second person to be eliminated despite never receiving a vote against him, after Michael Skupin in The Australian Outback.

Paschal is the first person to be eliminated by rocks, followed by Katie Collins in Blood vs. Water and Jessica Lewis in Millennials vs. Gen X.
He is currently the only male with this feat.

Had current rules involving drawing rocks applied in his season, Paschal would have been eliminated anyway, seeing as how the player with individual immunity (Vecepia Towery) and the two players in a deadlock tie (Kathy Vavrick-O'Brien and Neleh) would be safe from the draw, meaning that Paschal would have been automatically eliminated by default.

Paschal's elimination via the purple rock affected the subsequent seasons of Survivor. Due to contestants not wanting to force a tied vote, there would not be another tie until "The Best and Worst Reward Ever" in Palau, six seasons later.

Excluding those who were evacuated or quit the competition, Paschal is the first castaway who did not have his name written down on parchment over the course of a season. He was followed by Jonathan Libby and Wanda Shirk in Palau, Sugar Kiper in Gabon, Rupert Boneham in Blood vs. Water, and Cirie Fields in Game Changers.
Paschal is the only jury member to miss a Tribal Council. He was unable to attend the Day 38 Tribal Council because he was hospitalized.
Neleh's name (pronounced Neh-lee-yah) comes from her grandmother's name, Helen, spelled backwards.
Neleh's luxury item was Scriptures.
Neleh is the first contestant from Utah.

Neleh was the youngest contestant in Survivor: Marquesas.
Neleh was the first finalist to be the youngest contestant in their season. She was followed by Jenna Morasca in The Amazon, Aras Baskauskas in Panama, Natalie Tenerelli in Redemption Island, and Spencer Bledsoe in Cambodia.
Neleh is the first Survivor contestant who was born in the 1980s.
Neleh and Paschal English voted for the same person at every Tribal Council they attended.

Neleh is the highest placing member of Rotu.
Neleh was the first runner-up to be the highest-ranking member of a tribe.
Neleh is currently the last finalist to have her torch snuffed at the live finale.
In a Survivor Oz interview, Neleh said that her favorite contestant is Twila Tanner and her favorite winner is Rob Mariano.
Vecepia's Luxury Item was a notebook of poetry that she wrote.

Vecepia, along with Rob Mariano and Sean Rector are the first contestants to be on a tribe with every castaway on their season.
They are also the only one to do so on a season with only two pre-merge tribes.

Vecepia was the first female to celebrate her birthday during the game. This happened during "The Princess".
Coincidentally, Richard Hatch, the first male to celebrate his birthday during the game, went on to win as well.

Vecepia was the first African-American woman to win an individual Immunity Challenge.
Vecepia would become the first African-American to win individual immunity multiple times. The next time this would happen would be 15 seasons later in Samoa when Jaison Robinson won two consecutive Immunity Challenges.

Vecepia became the series' first African-American finalist and later the first African-American winner. In the latter feat, Vecepia was followed by Earl Cole in Fiji, Jeremy Collins in Survivor: Cambodia, and Wendell Holland in Survivor: Ghost Island.
Vecepia is also the first African-American to win a reality show.

Vecepia was the first Sole Survivor to win multiple individual Immunity Challenges.
She is also the first female Sole Survivor to win individual immunity.
She is the first Sole Survivor to win against someone of her own gender at the Final Tribal Council.
Vecepia became the first winner to win against someone who started on the opposing tribe.
Vecepia is the first Sole Survivor to be on every tribe in the season they won.
Throughout her entire time in Survivor, Vecepia has never been on reward or won a Reward Challenge, making her the first finalist, and winner, with this distinction.
Vecepia is the only female from the original Maraamu to make the merge.
John's luxury item was a Christian flag.
John and Clay Jordan were the first contestants from Louisiana.
John had the first confessional of Survivor: Thailand.
John cast the first vote in Survivor: Thailand.
Tanya's luxury item was a hairbrush.
Tanya was the youngest member of the Chuay Gahn tribe and the only member in their 20's at the time of filming.
In 2014, Tanya was nominated for The Ozcars in the "Best Second Boot" category. She won by popular vote, beating Billy Garcia and Russell Hantz.
Jed's luxury item was a frisbee.
Jed was the only member of Sook Jai not to outlast exactly three members of Chuay Gahn, being voted out between the second and third Chuay Gahn members.
At the Survivor: Thailand Reunion Show, it was revealed by Shii Ann that Sook Jai deliberately threw the Immunity Challenge in order to get rid of Jed.
Ghandia's luxury item was a lucky key chain.
When Clay Jordan voted her out he put "Bye Bye Denver Diva." This action annoyed Jeff Probst, as he could not figure out who the vote was for.
Despite being the fourth person out, Ghandia was featured on the season's DVD cover.
Ghandia is the only member of Chuay Gahn to outlast an odd number (1) of Sook Jai members.
Stephanie's luxury item were fuzzy slippers.
Stephanie was the first female to be selected to be on a tribe in a Schoolyard Pick.
Stephanie was the oldest woman on Sook Jai.
Stephanie is the first female to be disqualified from a challenge.
Stephanie was the first female voted out of Sook Jai.
Both times Stephanie went to Tribal Council, she voted against Shii Ann.
Starting with Stephanie, everyone who was on Sook Jai would be voted out until none were left.

Her audition tape, in which she appears naked, was shown at the Reunion Show. Jeff said that he was really disappointed with her performance on the show because after watching her tape he expected her to be a more interesting contestant.

Robb was the youngest contestant on Thailand.
Robb is the first male to be the youngest contestant in a season.
Robb is the first person to be the youngest contestant in a season and not make it to the merge.

Robb's luxury item was a skateboard.
According to his Survivor Oz interview, the skateboard was not his first choice. Originally, he chose pen and paper, but Jake Billingsley already brought those. His second choice was a football, but Boston Rob had that the season prior. Annoyed, Robb jokingly asked what was he suppose to bring, sarcastically saying he will bring a skateboard. The producers then decided that would be his luxury item.
At every Tribal Council Robb went to, he voted against Shii Ann Huang.
Despite being voted out before the merge, Robb was featured on the season's DVD cover.
Robb was nominated for Survivor: America's Tribal Council in the "Sexiest Male" category, but lost to Colby Donaldson.
Robb was on the show ElimiDate, according to his interview with Survivor Oz. Robb described it as a terrible dating show. Also during said interview, one of the people said he should go on Survivor.
Erin's luxury item was body paint.
Erin is the youngest female on Thailand.
Erin is the first jury member who was not part of a merged tribe.
Erin was nominated for Survivor: America's Tribal Council in the "Hottest Female" category, but lost to Amber Brkich.
Ken's luxury item was a NYPD shield.
Ken was the first person in Survivor history to be disqualified from a challenge for breaking the challenge rules.
Penny's luxury item was a pair of pajamas.
Penny was the first contestant to cry after another contestant was voted out.
Penny was the youngest member of Chuay Jai and the only member below the age of thirty.
Penny is the highest ranking Sook Jai female.
Penny was the only female from Sook Jai to be a member of Chuay Jai.
Penny only received votes at tribal when she was voting against members of her own tribe.
Penny was the only member of Sook Jai to make the merge but not receive all of the votes of the former Chuay Gahn tribe.
Jake's luxury item was a journal and pen.
Jake was the oldest contestant in Thailand.
Jake is the oldest castaway that did not compete in Survivor: Borneo.
Jake is the first male castaway to pick his entire tribe in a Schoolyard Pick.

Jake was the last Sook Jai member standing in Thailand.
Jake become the first man to become the highest-ranking member of their original tribe by virtue of every other member being eliminated from the competition. Both Richard Hatch and Ethan Zohn became the highest-ranking members of their starting tribes by winning the game against an original member of their tribe.
Jake is the only member of Sook Jai to vote for Brian Heidik to win.
Jake won a people's choice award for being the most popular contestant on Thailand.
Ted's luxury item was a shaving kit. He did not use it to shave his facial hair, and instead shaved his head, once every three days.
Ted was on the Dallas Cowboys' 1994 preseason roster but was cut before the season started.
Ted was the first person to be selected by Schoolyard Pick.
Ted is the first contestant to write a single letter in casting a vote for Ghandia Johnson at the time of her elimination.
Ted is the first Chuay Gahn member to be voted off unanimously.
Helen's luxury item was her daughter's doll.
Helen is the only Chuay Gahn member to sit out from a challenge.
Helen is the only female to win an individual challenge during Thailand.
She was the oldest female contestant on Thailand and the oldest member of Chuay Gahn.
Jan's cover story for her time on Survivor was that she was taking care of her sick mother.
Jan is the first female castaway to pick her entire tribe.
During her time in Thailand, she constructed her own pet cemetery. It contained a baby bat and parts of a chicken.
Among the five Chuay Gahn members that made it to the merge, Jan was the only one who never won an individual challenge.
Jan never received more than one vote at any Tribal Council.
Jan was the first castaway to finish in 3rd place but not win individual immunity.
Jan is the first contestant to hug and kiss Jeff Probst after having been voted out; Sarah Dawson of Survivor: Philippines would later do the same thing.
Jan once applied for The Amazing Race with her step-daughter.
Clay and John Raymond are the first contestants from Louisiana.
Clay's luxury items were a golf club and a ball.
Clay is the first male to be placed on a tribe by default after a Schoolyard Pick as he was not picked by either Jan Gentry or Jake Billingsley.
Clay was the oldest male on Chuay Gahn.

In "Gender Bender", Clay cast a vote against Ghandia Johnson and wrote, "Bye Bye Denver Diva". Host Jeff Probst did not know who the vote was for and had to ask who cast it and who they voted for. After this incident, Jeff made it official that only identifiable nicknames should be written on votes.
Clay is the first player to lose the Final Immunity Challenge and finish as runner-up.
Jake Billingsley was the only Sook Jai member not to vote for Clay to become the Sole Survivor.

Clay is the first person to receive a jury vote from someone he was never on the same tribe with, namely Erin Collins.
Although most finalists before Survivor: Thailand received jury votes from people who they were not on the same starting tribe with pre-merge, they were all a part of the merged tribe.
Coincidentally, Clay and Erin were the first contestants to be placed on a tribe by virtue of being the last people remaining after a Schoolyard Pick.
Brian's luxury item was a guitar.

Brian is the only castaway to never receive an elimination vote against him in Survivor: Thailand.
Brian is the third winner not to get any votes against him at Tribal Council. The first two are Tina Wesson and Ethan Zohn.
Brian is the first person to win the Final Immunity Challenge and then become the Sole Survivor.
Brian was the first male to win multiple individual Immunity Challenges and become the Sole Survivor.

Brian was the first person to win the most individual Immunity Challenges of their season and become the Sole Survivor, although Vecepia Towery tied for most individual immunity wins in her season with two.
Brian was the first male to win against a male finalist at Final Tribal Council.
Brian was the youngest male member of Chuay Gahn.
Brian was called back for Survivor: All-Stars, but he said he would not come back unless he was paid a certain sum of money no matter what place he would finish.
Brian was a former actor in soft-core adult movies, starring in Sinful Obsession (1999) and The Virgins of Sherwood Forest (2000).
Brian was considered for Heroes vs. Villains, but the producers were too "repulsed" by him to bring him back.
Brian is the only Thailand castaway to not attend the Survivor 10-year anniversary party.
Brian appeared in a couple commercials for the Crispy Crunch candy bar in the early 1990s.
Ryan's luxury item was a baseball and bat.
Ryan is the first contestant from Maryland.

The episode in which he was eliminated aired on his 24th birthday.
Ryan was the first contestant to have a season premiere air on their birthday. This would not happen again until the first episode of Survivor: Cagayan first aired on David Samson's 46th birthday.
Coincidentally, they were both voted off first.
Ryan was the first contestant to be voted out of a tribe initially made up of one single gender.
Ryan was the first person under the age of 40 who ended up being the first person voted out of a season.
Being 23 at the time of filming, Ryan is tied with Jonathan Libby for being the youngest person to be the first person eliminated from a season.
Janet was the oldest female contestant on The Amazon.

Janet was the second Survivor contestant (following Kel Gleason) that was accused of smuggling food into the game.
Coincidentally, both Janet and Kel were the second castaways to be voted out of their respective seasons, as well as the first castaways to be voted out of their respective tribes.
Janet's luxury item was her daughter's teddy bear.
Janet and Heidi Strobel are the first contestants from the state of Missouri.
Daniel is the first male Asian-American to play Survivor and second overall Asian-American player, preceded by Shii Ann Huang.
Daniel's luxury item was a pair of magnetic rings.
Both times Daniel went to Tribal Council, he voted against Roger and received votes from Dave.
Daniel was able to speak Mandarin with Matthew von Ertfelda, who lived in Hong Kong and is fluent in the language.
JoAnna's luxury item was a picture of her mother.
JoAnna was mentioned in the "Business Ethics" episode in season five of The Office by the character Ryan, claiming he "hooked up with a girl that looked just like her" in New York City.
Jeanne's luxury item was a bottle of massage oil.
Jeanne had the most confessionals of all of the pre-jury boots on The Amazon.
Jeanne is the second person and first female to switch tribes and be voted out before the merge. Silas from Africa was the first.
According to Survivor Oz, Shawna claims that she was closest with Jeanne during her time on The Amazon.
Shawna's luxury item was a soccer ball.
During the Reward Challenge in "Girl Power", Daniel Lue implied that he had a crush on Shawna.
Though she did not ultimately do so, Shawna was the first player to be shown considering quitting.

Roger was the oldest castaway in Survivor: The Amazon.
Roger was the first castaway to be the oldest of the season but not make it to the jury phase of the game.
His luxury item were dog tags.
Roger had the most votes cast against him in The Amazon, with 11.
Dave's luxury items was a croquis.

In "Pick-Up Sticks", the first Tree Mail told both tribes to send their youngest player to a summit. Even though Dave was the youngest member of Tambaqui at the time, Ryan Aiken, who was voted out first, was four weeks younger than him.
Dave and fellow Tambaqui member Ryan Aiken went to high school in the same city at the same year. Their schools were only 4.1 miles (6.4 km) from each other.
Deena's luxury items were water balloons.
Deena only voted against females before the merge and only voted against males after the merge.
Deena is the first Hispanic-American contestant to last longer than 6 days in the game.
Deena is the only Amazon jury member to never be a member of Tambaqui.
Alex was nominated in Survivor: America's Tribal Council as "Sexiest Male", but lost to Colby Donaldson.
His luxury item was a triathlon medal he won.
Alex is the only Survivor: The Amazon contestant to write Matthew von Ertfelda's name down more than once at Tribal Council.
Christy is the first Survivor deaf contestant. She would be followed by Nina Poersch.
Christy's luxury item was a vial of sage.
Heidi and Janet Koth are the first contestants from the state of Missouri.
Heidi initially applied for The Amazing Race with her grandfather as her partner, but due to Mark Burnett's insistence, she applied for Survivor instead.
Heidi became the first person to receive the Immunity Necklace from the original winner of the Immunity Challenge.
Heidi's luxury item was skipping rope.
Heidi says living in The Amazon took a toll on her health. She incurred spider bites, parasites that hurt her kidneys, and significant weight loss.
She was nominated in Survivor: America's Tribal Council in the Sexiest Female category, but lost to Amber Brkich.
Butch is the first contestant from Illinois.
Butch's luxury item was a "Believe in Yourself" banner.
Matthew is the first contestant from Washington, D.C.
Fluent in Mandarin, Matthew frequently spoke the language with tribemate Daniel Lue.
Matthew is the first person to only garner a single jury vote at Final Tribal Council and Matthew is the first male finalist to gain less than three jury votes at Final Tribal Council.
Because the contestants entered the game with the clothes on their back, Nicole spent her time in the game without a bra.
Nicole is the only person to be on two different tribes in a season and be eliminated first.

Nicole is the first first boot to have won a challenge.
Nicole is also the first first boot to spend more than three days in the game.
Ryan S. is the youngest male in the Pearl Islands
Ryan S. is also the tallest contestant on Pearl Islands.
While The Outcasts tribe didn't have an official buff, they had pieces of purple fabric as their unofficial one; Ryan S. wrote "Die Jerks" on his.
Ryan S. was the only male to be permanently eliminated during the Outcast twist.
Ryan S. voted for both of the eventual returnees from The Outcasts tribe, Lillian Morris and Burton Roberts.
Ryan S. received votes at every Tribal Council he attended, including the Outcast vote.
Michelle was the youngest member of the Drake tribe.
Trish was the oldest member of the Drake tribe.
Shawn was the youngest male on Drake.
Shawn is the first person to be voted out on Day 19.
Shawn was the only person in Pearl Islands that was voted out pre-merge to not be a part of The Outcasts twist.
Osten is the first contestant to quit Survivor.

Osten became the first Survivor to not have his final words aired at the end of the episode. Only shots of marine life were shown as the credits were rolling, with the final shot shown being Osten's extinguished torch lying on the ground. The torch remained lain at Tribal Council for the rest of the season and was not included in the Rites of Passage.
He was the first person who was not included in the Rites of Passage.
In an interview, Osten revealed that he quit the game because he had multiple staph infections, and claiming that Mark Burnett "quit on them" by introducing The Outcasts.
With Sandra Diaz-Twine voted out in Game Changers, Osten is the last castaway from Pearl Islands to never be voted out.
Ryan originally applied for Survivor: The Australian Outback and was an alternate for Africa, Thailand, and The Amazon before being cast on Pearl Islands.
Tijuana was voted out one day short of her 27th birthday.
Tijuana went by her nickname "T".
Tijuana was the first woman who was voted out by someone they had previously voted out.
Tijuana was the first female jury member in Pearl Islands.

Tijuana was the only jury member to vote Lillian Morris to win Survivor: Pearl Islands, preventing Sandra Diaz-Twine from having the first "perfect game" in Survivor: Pearl Islands (i.e. never receiving votes against and receiving all jury votes in a season). This also made her the first woman to be the only person to vote for a single finalist.
She is also the first and only jury member to vote for a finalist who was voted out and reentered the game.
She currently holds the record for the most weight carried in the Water Torture challenge by a woman with 160 lbs.
Christa's oldest daughter, Mischa Waydo, competed on the reality cooking show Chopped Junior in 2017 and won the top prize of $10,000.
Christa was the only female juror from the Drake tribe.
Burton and Lillian Morris are the first two people to return to the game after being voted out.

Burton was the first person to possess two individual immunities simultaneously (he had immunity as a returning Outcast and as the winner of an Immunity Challenge).
He is also the only castaway to give up immunity and not be left vulnerable. Burton is also the only one to not be the youngest contestant on the season.
He is the only player to give up individual immunity and not receive votes.
In "The Great Lie", Burton became the first person to win individual immunity, only to have it stripped.

Burton became the first person to be voted off more than once in a single season. He was the only one with this "distinction" for seven years, until Matt Elrod and Andrea Boehlke were voted off from Survivor: Redemption Island twice in 2011. Their "record" was broken when Ozzy Lusth was voted out three times on Survivor: South Pacific.
Burton remains the only person voted off more than once in a non-Redemption Island season.
Burton was nominated in Survivor: America's Tribal Council in the Sexiest Male category, but lost to Colby Donaldson.
Burton is tied with Lillian Morris to have the most votes cast against him in Survivor: Pearl Islands with 10.
Burton is the only Outcast who voted for two contestants of the same gender at the episode 8 returnee vote.
Darrah was the youngest contestant in Pearl Islands.
Darrah is the first, and so far only, Survivor contestant from Mississippi.

Darrah won three successive individual Immunity Challenges, only one short of Kelly Wiglesworth's record of four in a row in Borneo.
She was the first of two people to be voted out in the first Tribal Council in which she was eligible, immediately following three immunity wins.
Tasha Fox is the second to do so, in Cagayan.

Darrah was referenced in Survivor: All-Stars, during a quiz-type Immunity Challenge about the show's first seven seasons. The question about her was "In "Pearl Islands", who was the mortician?" This prompted Lex van den Berghe to say "I remember Darrah!"
Darrah also went by the nickname "D".
Darrah was planning to go on The Amazing Race. However, her partner, a friend, backed out at the last minute.

Lillian was the oldest contestant in Pearl Islands.
Lillian is the second of five oldest contestants to make it to the Final Tribal Council. The first was Kim Johnson and they were followed by Phillip Sheppard (in Redemption Island), Carolyn Rivera, and Troyzan Robertson (in Game Changers).
Lillian is the first contestant from Ohio.
When Lillian was voted out, her torch did not go out on the first try.
Lillian and Burton Roberts are the first two castaways to return to the game after being voted out.
Once she reentered the game, Lillian voted for the person who left at every Tribal Council (Andrew Savage and all seven members of the jury).

Lillian is the only player to return into the game after being voted out (either from the Outcasts twist or Redemption Island) and make it to the Final Tribal Council. Burton Roberts was eliminated prior to the final two in Pearl Islands, Matt Elrod and Andrea Boehlke were voted out at the immediate Tribal Council after returning in Redemption Island, Ozzy Lusth returned twice in Survivor: South Pacific, but was officially eliminated right before the final three, and Laura Morett and Tina Wesson were both eliminated shortly after their returns in Survivor: Blood vs. Water.

Lillian is the only contestant to reach a Final Tribal Council without being in the game for the entire 39 days, only staying in the game for 30 days, discounting the days in between her ejection from Morgan and her return as an Outcast.
Lillian is tied with Burton Roberts for most votes cast against her in Pearl Islands, with 10.
Lillian was voted "biggest goat" by Survivor Oz.
Brook was one of four castaways who has been confirmed to have been cast by Kelly Goldsmith for Vanuatu.

Brook is the first male contestant to finish in 18th place.
He is also the first new contestant to finish in 18th place, as the 18th-place finisher in Survivor: All-Stars was a returnee.
Dolly is the first new player to finish in 17th place, as the 17th-place finisher in Survivor: All-Stars was a returnee.
John was the first person to be voted out on Day 7. Mia Galeotalanza was also voted out on Day 7, but Lopevi went to Tribal Council first.
Mia was the first female contestant to be voted out on Day 7. The first overall was John Palyok, who was voted out moments before her.
Brady was one of four castaways that were confirmed to have been casted by Kelly Goldsmith for Vanuatu.
Brady voted for Rory at every Tribal Council he attended.
Brady was the first person to be voted out on Day 10.
In his official cast photo, Brady is wearing a shirt that says "Boran", which was the name of a tribe in Survivor: Africa.
Brady is the first contestant voted out of Survivor: Vanuatu to not have had five votes cast against him.
Brady said his cover story was that he was being sent on an Temporary Bureau Assignment.
Bubba was the first man to have a confessional in Vanuatu. He stated in said confessional that he learned to swim shortly before the show started.
During the game, Bubba wore a T-shirt with the face of Bob Barker.
Bubba is the only player who switched tribes to be voted off pre-merge in Vanuatu.
Lisa is the first contestant to not be picked in a tribal switch and given the option of choosing either tribe.
John is the youngest male contestant on Survivor: Vanuatu.
John is the first castaway to win a pre-merge individual Immunity Challenge.
John was the only castaway to be voted out of the post-switch Lopevi tribe.
Rory received votes at all six Tribal Councils he attended. He also holds the record for the number of straight Tribal Councils attended and receiving votes with 6.

Rory received 14 votes against him during Vanuatu, breaking the former record of most votes cast against someone in a single season of 12, set by Jerri Manthey in Survivor: The Australian Outback and tied by Lindsey Richter and Clarence Black in Survivor: Africa. The record would later be broken by Survivor: Cook Islands contestant Jonathan Penner with 15 votes. The current record holder for most votes accumulated in a single season is Laura Morett when she gotten 19 votes in Survivor: Blood vs. Water.

Rory is the first contestant from Iowa.
Fellow Survivor: Vanuatu contestant, Twila Tanner, was also born in Iowa, but did not live there at the time of filming.
Rory accidentally broke the Tribal Immunity Idol while sticking it into the ground.
In the season premiere of Vanuatu, when the local tribesman surround the castaways with spears, Rory noted that he was the only one who didn't have a spear pointed at him.
Rory was the only male contestant on Vanuatu to be on all three tribes.
Lea was the oldest male contestant on Survivor: Vanuatu.
Lea is the first male contestant from South Carolina.
Lea is the lowest ranking Alinta member to win individual immunity.
Lea and Travis Sampson are the first ever contestants to be referred to by a nickname/alternate name (Sarge) throughout their time in the game.
Chad is the first amputee to compete on Survivor. He would later be followed by Survivor: Nicaragua contestant Kelly Bruno.
Despite placing 8th, Chad was the last male contestant to be voted out of Survivor: Vanuatu, as the only man to outlast him reached the Final Tribal Council and ultimately won the game.
An earthquake occurred during one of Leann's confessionals.
Julie was one of four castaways that were confirmed to have been casted by former survivor turned casting agent Kelly Goldsmith for Survivor: Vanuatu.
By virtue of having dated Jeff Probst, Julie implied she may be perpetually ineligible to compete in future seasons, as she had known production secrets.
Julie was a student of Survivor: Gabon winner Bob Crowley.
Scout is the first Survivor contestant from Oklahoma.
Scout was the oldest contestant on Survivor: Vanuatu.
Scout has an artificial knee, which is the main reason she consistently fell behind in challenges.
Scout was the one that came up with the name Alinta for the merged tribe on Survivor: Vanuatu.
She is the oldest woman to be the last person voted out of a season.
Scout is the first woman to be the oldest castaway of the season but not make it to Final Tribal Council.

Scout became the first person to be the sixteenth person voted out of a season. Although Jenna Lewis in All-Stars was the first person overall to be the sixteenth person eliminated from a season, two people quit in All-Stars.
Out of all LGBT female contestants, Scout has lasted the longest within a season, making it to Day 38 and placing 3rd.
While she has been identified as a lesbian in the media, Scout says she is actually interested in both genders, describing herself as "omnisexual".
Every time Twila received votes against her, Eliza was one of them.
According to the CBS polls, Chris is the most popular contestant from Survivor: Vanuatu. Early on however, Ami Cusack was the fan favorite up until the merge due to her scheming.
Chris is the first male Sole Survivor to defeat a castaway from the opposing tribe in the finals.
Chris broke the streak of three consecutive seasons being won by women. Ironically, from "Surprise and... Surprise Again!" onward, he was the only man left.

Chris is the only winner to receive votes at the first Tribal Council of the season.
Jenna Morasca and Sophie Clarke also received votes the first time they went to Tribal Council, but did not attend the first Tribal Council of their respective seasons.
According to his testimonial on "The Funny 115", Chris claimed he yelled "f*** yeah" after he won. He also claimed that the shirt he wore throughout the game was planned by CBS, not by him.
Chris is the first of only three winners to vote against the majority of the tribe during the first Tribal Council after the merge, the others being Danni Boatwright and Bob Crowley.
Since he was left unpicked before Wanda Shirk, Jonathan is the first contestant to finish in 20th place.
Jonathan and Wanda are the only contestants to never be assigned to a tribe.
Jonathan is included as a member of Ulong in the opening credits, since if the Schoolyard Pick continued, he would have been placed on Ulong by default.

Jonathan is one of six contestants to never go to Tribal Council, along with Wanda, Kourtney Moon, Gary Stritesky, Dana Lambert, and Pat Cusack.
Jonathan, Wanda, Kourtney, and Pat are the only contestants to be eliminated from the game in the first episode by means other than a vote.

Jonathan, along with Paschal English, Wanda, Sugar Kiper in Gabon, Rupert Boneham in Blood vs. Water, and Cirie Fields in Game Changers, is one of six castaways (excluding evacuees and quitters) to never have a vote cast for or against them over the course of a season.
Wanda was the oldest female contestant in Survivor: Palau.
Wanda and Jonathan Libby are the only contestants to never be assigned to a tribe.
Wanda and Jonathan are the only two contestants to be eliminated on Day 2.
As Jonathan was left unpicked before her, Wanda is the first person to finish in 19th place. The first voted out player to come in 19th place was Billy Garcia.

Wanda and Jonathan became the first two castaways to never visit Tribal Council. They were followed by Gary Stritesky, Kourtney Moon, Dana Lambert. and Pat Cusack.
Wanda, Jonathan, Kourtney, and Pat are the only contestants to be eliminated from the game in the first episode by means other than a vote.
Wanda is included as a member of Koror in the opening credits, since she would have been the tribe's last choice.
At the Palau Live Reunion Show, Wanda sang her own original Survivor song.

Wanda, along with Paschal English, Jonathan Libby, Sugar Kiper in Survivor: Gabon, Rupert Boneham in Survivor: Blood vs. Water, and Cirie Fields in Survivor: Game Changers, is one of five castaways (excluding evacuees and quitters) to never have a vote cast for or against them over the course of a season.
Wanda is one of three castaways to never receive a vote cast against them in Survivor: Palau, the others being are Jonathan Libby and Tom Westman.

Jolanda is the only Ulong member and the only female in Palau to win individual immunity in a challenge.
Ibrehem Rahman of Ulong also possessed individual immunity, but it was granted to him by a vote.

Jolanda is one of five African-American females to win individual immunity.
The others are Vecepia Towery, Tasha Fox, Cydney Gillon, and Desi Williams.
Unlike the other four, Jolanda's immunity did not make her safe at Tribal Council.

Jolanda was the first female contestant in Palau to be part of a tribe.
The first overall was Ian Rosenberger, who won the men's immunity before she won the women's immunity.
Jolanda was the first person voted out and the third one eliminated, while Ian was the last person voted out and placed 3rd.
Jolanda was the oldest contestant on Ulong.

Jolanda is the first contestant to be voted out first, but not be eliminated first because of Jonathan Libby and Wanda Shirk being eliminated by not being chosen to be on a tribe.
She was followed by Nina Acosta in One World, Laura Boneham in Blood vs. Water, and Jessica Peet in David vs. Goliath.
Jolanda is the lowest-ranking castaway to possess individual immunity.

Jolanda is the first contestant to win individual immunity and be voted out at the next Tribal Council. She was followed by Erik Reichenbach and Brandon Hantz.
Jolanda, Erik, Jim Rice, Brandon, and Andrea Boehlke are the only contestants to win individual immunity and be voted out in the same episode, excluding season finales.
Including season finales, Rafe Judkins, Yau-Man Chan (in Fiji), Brett Clouser, Ashley Underwood, Ozzy Lusth (in South Pacific), Kass McQuillen (in Cagayan), Keith Nale (in San Juan del Sur), Kelley Wentworth (in Cambodia), and David Wright were also voted out in the same episode that they won immunity.
Jolanda was the first contestant to have an individual challenge win but no tribal challenge win. She was the only contestant with this distinction before Redemption Island.
Ashlee is the youngest female contestant on Survivor: Palau.
Jeff was the youngest contestant on Survivor: Palau.
Jeff is the lowest placing male member of the Ulong tribe.
Although he did not quit, he is the first male to ask to be voted out, and the second person overall to do so, following Shawna Mitchell from Survivor: The Amazon.
Kim is the first person on Survivor: Palau to be voted off unanimously.
Kim is the first Miss Ohio USA winner to play Survivor, the second being Candace Smith of Tocantins.
Kim is tied with Stephenie LaGrossa, Angie Jakusz, and Willard Smith for the most votes received in Survivor: Palau, with 8.
A joke that is believed to be originated from the Survivor fan community states that the Immunity Idol for Palau looked like Willard, earning it the nickname "The Immunity Willard".

Willard was the only member of Koror to be eliminated during the tribal stage of the game.
However, he was eliminated at a Double Tribal Council.
Willard was the oldest contestant on Palau.

While in Palau, Willard said that he was a mail carrier, not a lawyer.
However, he revealed in the reunion that he was a mail carrier at one point.
Willard is tied with Angie Jakusz, Kim Mullen, and Stephenie LaGrossa for the most votes received in Palau with 8.
Angie was voted out the same night as the ninth person picked for the Koror tribe.
Angie is tied with Stephenie LaGrossa, Kim Mullen, and Willard Smith for the most votes received in Survivor: Palau with 8.
Angie is the first contestant to receive more votes in a revote than in the original vote.
James was the oldest male contestant on Ulong and the only one in his 30s.
James and tribemates Bobby Jon Drinkard and Ibrehem Rahman are the first Survivor contestants from the state of Alabama.
When the Koror tribe found out that James was voted out they quoted his famous lines, "you ain't lyin'" and "come on".
Ibrehem and two of his tribemates, Bobby Jon Drinkard and James Miller, are the first Survivor contestants from the state of Alabama.

Ibrehem Rahman is the first castaway of Muslim faith.
He would be followed by Natalia Azoqa from Survivor: David vs. Goliath.
Ibrehem was the only Ulong member to have immunity at a Tribal Council (Jolanda Jones of Ulong also won individual immunity, but didn't have it at Tribal Council).

He is the first, and so far only, contestant to receive immunity via an immunity vote from the opposite tribe.
Ozzy Lusth and Alexis Jones from Survivor: Micronesia also received immunity via vote, though those two votes were not official immunity votes.
Ami Cusack and Gary Hogeboom also received individual immunity via an immunity vote, although only one person voted, instead of the whole tribe.
He was the first contestant to be eliminated from a tribe of 3 in the tribal phase of the game. The second is Russell Swan.
Before being voted out, Koror gave Coby an oar from their boat in respect of him. The oar was taken away by production.
Coby is the only juror in Palau to vote for Katie, thus preventing Tom from achieving a "Perfect Game".
After filming was wrapped, production gave Coby the recipe of the beef stew they ate during their reward in "The Best and Worst Reward Ever".
Coby claims he was considered for Survivor: Micronesia but was cut when the season was changed from an All-Stars season to a Fans vs. Favorites.
Janu is the first castaway in Survivor history to be banished to Exile Island.
Janu is the lowest ranking female Koror tribemate.
Janu is the first player to quit at the jury stage of the game.
Janu is the only player to quit specifically to save another player.
Janu is the first player to quit and still have her closing speech aired.
Janu has won the most challenges out of any one who has quit the game with 12.
Fellow Koror tribemate, Coby Archa, named his adopted daughter after Janu.
Coby Archa claims that Janu was considered for Survivor: Micronesia, but was not chosen.

Janu is responsible for the inclusion of NaOnka Mixon and Kelly Shinn on the jury upon quitting in Survivor: Nicaragua. Jeff explained that "We had set a precedent. We let Janu stay on the jury so we let NaOnka and Purple Kelly on the jury as well".
Gregg lost 26 lbs. (11.8 kg) during his time in Palau.
Caryn was the oldest female member of Koror.
In "I'll Show You How Threatening I Am", Caryn used tribemate Stephenie LaGrossa's old Ulong buff as a bikini bottom.
Jenn and Ian are the first contestants to partake in a final four fire making challenge due to a deadlocked vote.
Because Palau was the first season with 20 contestants, Jenn was the first castaway to be the 17th person to be eliminated in a season.
In their profiles for Survivor: Heroes vs. Villains, both Stephenie LaGrossa and Tom Westman have stated that Jenn is the past Survivor castaway that they respected the most.
Jenn was good friends with Jeff Probst, and he would sometimes drive her to the hospital.

Ian is the fourth-tallest Survivor contestant, at 6'8" (207 cm). He is just short of Cliff Robinson, Scot Pollard, and Mitchell Olson, who are 6' 10" (208 cm), 6' 11" (210 cm), and 7 feet (213 cm) respectively.
Ian was the youngest member of Koror.

Ian was the first male to win the fire making tiebreaker. Ian was also the first castaway to win a fire making challenge at the final four as Stephenie LaGrossa won her fire making challenge as a result of Ulong being decimated to its last two members.

Ian is the first of three contestants to have been verbally voted out, without a formal vote taking place. He would be followed by Brandon Hantz in Survivor: Caramoan and Jeff Varner in Survivor: Game Changers.
Because Palau was the first season with 20 castaways, Ian was the first castaway to be the 18th person eliminated from a season.
Ian was offered a chance to return for Survivor: Cambodia, but he declined.
Katie originally auditioned for Survivor: Africa, but was cut. She later said she was glad she was cut that season because she wasn't sure if she would have lasted.
Katie was the youngest female member of Koror.
Katie was the first runner-up to make it to Final Tribal Council without winning individual immunity.
Katie is the only finalist to only be on one tribe in her Survivor career.
Jim was the oldest castaway on Guatemala.
At the age of 63, Jim is the oldest male contestant to be the first person voted out of an season. Jim is tied with Sonja Christopher for the oldest overall.

Jim is the first contestant to win a Reward Challenge, but be the first person voted out.
Jim is also the first contestant to win a challenge with their original tribe, but be the first person voted out. Nicole Delma in Survivor: Pearl Islands won as an Outcast, while Jolanda Jones in Survivor: Palau won an individual challenge before tribes were formed.
Morgan originally applied for Big Brother, but was cast for Survivor instead.
Morgan is the youngest castaway in Survivor: Guatemala.
Morgan McDevitt, Morgan McLeod and Morgan Ricke are the only contestants to have the same name as a tribe (Morgan of Survivor: Pearl Islands).
Brooke was the youngest female from Nakúm.
Brooke wound up on Nakúm during the tribe switch by chance, as the remaining Nakúm members had to draw for a buff to even out the tribes.

In an interview on Survivor Oz, Brooke claimed she formed an early alliance with Danni, Margaret, Cindy, Brandon, and Bobby Jon, and that Judd and Blake would have been the next to go had no tribe switch occurred.
Blake's nickname in Guatemala was The Golden Boy because "no matter what happened to him, he always came out shining". The nickname was given to him by Amy O'Hara.
Blake is the first person to be voted out on Day 14.
Of the eight castaways from Guatemala that switched tribes during the Tribe Switch, Blake is the only one who did not make the merge.
Of the castaways who were voted off of Yaxhá, Blake's elimination was the only one that was not unanimous.
Margaret was the oldest female castaway from Survivor: Guatemala.
Margaret received her first vote from Jim as a result of drawing the shortest straw at the Nakúm camp earlier on Day 3, as Jim knew he would be leaving.
Both times Margaret received votes at Tribal Council, the result was a unanimous vote.
Margaret is known for being the nurse of the Nakúm tribe (mostly when other contestants weren't feeling well).
Brian was the youngest male in Guatemala.
Brian had the first confessional in Guatemala.
Amy was a replacement contestant, replacing Tina Scheer, who backed out because of her son's death. Scheer reapplied for the following season, Survivor: Panama, and made it onto the show.
Amy is the one who gave Blake Towsley the nickname Golden Boy.
Brandon is the youngest member of Nakúm.
Jamie is one of three Guatemala castaways to have a twin. The others are Cindy Hall and Judd Sergeant.
Jamie is the lowest ranking member of the Xhakúm tribe to win an individual Immunity Challenge.
Jamie is the lowest placing post-swap Nakúm member to make the merge.
Jamie is tied with Lydia Morales for most votes received in Guatemala, with 10.
When Jamie won individual immunity on Day 24, the necklace was placed backwards on him.
Jamie states that he was a substitute for a player who broke his leg in a basketball game.
Although he used a false name while introducing himself as "Gary Hawkins" the landscaper, he did not lie about his profession, as landscaping was actually what he did at the time.

Gary was reluctant to reveal his real surname for fear that fellow castaways would recognize him as a former NFL player. At the Reunion Show, Danni Boatwright revealed that she knew who he was all along, being a sports-radio talk show host. She also revealed in a private conversation with Gary she recognized exactly who he was during the game, but kept her promise to keep it a secret from the rest of the castaways.
Gary was the oldest member of the Yaxhá tribe.
Gary is the first former NFL player to compete on Survivor, and would later be followed by Steve Wright, Grant Mattos, Alan Ball, Brad Culpepper, and Tyler Fredrickson.
Gary is the first contestant to find a Hidden Immunity Idol.

Gary is the first contestant to find the Hidden Immunity Idol without the aid of a legitimate clue. He got a false clue from Judd Sergeant, but found the idol after observing Judd when he was looking for it.

Gary was the only person that was a part of the merged tribe to be part of the Yaxhá tribe for the entire pre-merge stage of the game, and as such was the only member of Xhakúm to never be part of the Nakúm tribe.

The episode in which Gary was voted out is the only non-recap episode in Survivor history intended to air on Thanksgiving Day. Coincidentally, the episode aired immediately following an NFL game involving the Dallas Cowboys, Gary's former team.

Judd became the first person ever to receive a clue to the location of the Hidden Immunity Idol.
Despite this, Gary Hogeboom was the one who found it instead.

In the episode "Big Ball, Big Mouth, Big Trouble", Judd went on an approximate three-and-a-half minute rant about his trustworthiness at Tribal Council, during which he accused Margaret Bobonich of saying he had ADD, and Margaret said that she did not (in reality, it was true; it was actually Danni Boatwright who had said it).
Judd is one of three Guatemala castaways to have a twin. The others are Jamie Newton and Cindy Hall.
Judd is the only member of Xhakúm to never cast a vote against Jamie Newton.
Cindy is the first, and currently only, contestant to have the option of giving up a car reward and allowing the remaining competitors to each receive one instead.
Cindy is one of three Guatemala castaways to have a twin. The others are Jamie Newton and Judd Sergeant.

Her twin sister Mindy appeared on the third season of the VH1 hit show Rock of Love where she came in second place. Mindy also appeared on the fourth season of VH1's I Love Money where she eventually became the winner, taking home the prize of $250,000.
Despite being the sixth person voted out of Xhakúm, Cindy was the lowest placing woman of the tribe.
Cindy was the highest-placing Guatemala castaway to not switch tribes at the tribe switch.
Lydia was the oldest female member of the Yaxhá tribe.
Lydia is the only person in Survivor: Guatemala that voted against Danni Boatwright.
In the first episode of Guatemala, Lydia said she applied because of Stephenie's performance in Survivor: Palau.
Lydia is tied with Jamie Newton for having the most votes cast against her in Guatemala with 10.
Every time Lydia received votes against her, the person she voted for voted against her.
Rafe was the highest placing man on Guatemala.

Rafe was first castaway to win individual immunity in the finale and be voted out. He was followed by Yau-Man Chan, Brett Clouser, Ashley Underwood, Ozzy Lusth, Kass McQuillen, Keith Nale, and Kelley Wentworth.
Rafe won the most individual challenges of the season with four wins.
Rafe is the most recent person to cast an immunity vote, following the Koror tribe of Survivor: Palau.

Danni is the first contestant to win an advantage for an Immunity Challenge at a Survivor Auction.
She is also the first contestant to buy such an item and win the actual challenge.

Danni is the first first-time contestant to defeat a returning player at the Final Tribal Council
She would be followed by Sophie Clarke and Denise Stapley.
Danni is the second winner to be on every tribe in her season, after Vecepia of Survivor: Marquesas.
Danni is one of only four winners to vote against the majority of the tribe during the first Tribal Council after the merge, the others being Chris Daugherty, Bob Crowley, and Sarah Lacina.

Tina was supposed to be slated for Survivor: Guatemala, but backed out at the last minute because of her son's recent death. She was replaced by Amy O'Hara. Producers told her that when she was ready, she could skip the application process and they would put her on immediately.
Tina is the only contestant in Panama, and only female contestant in any season, to be eliminated during the four-tribes phase.
Tina's brother Rob competed in The Amazing Race 21 with his fiancée, Sheila. They were the first eliminated, placing 11th.
Tina Scheer is the second contestant named Tina to be the first voted out in a season, following Tina Wesson in All-Stars.
Melinda is the youngest castaway of the original Casaya tribe.

Melinda is the youngest person to be a member of an "older" tribe, at 32 years of age.
Interestingly, Bobby Mason, the oldest person to be a member of a "younger" tribe, was also 32 years old in Panama. However, Melinda is three months older than Bobby.
Melinda is the only woman to be eliminated post-swap and not be on La Mina.
Melinda lost all challenges that she competed in herself. The one challenge won by Casaya at the time was solely on Ruth-Marie Milliman.

Misty is the second person to be sent to Exile Island, following Janu Tornell from Survivor: Palau (where Exile Island was a one-episode only twist).
She is the first person to be sent to Exile Island in a season where it is a season-long twist.
Misty was the youngest woman on the post-switch La Mina tribe.
Of all castaways who have switched tribes, Misty has played the fewest number of days, with 8.
Misty was the only member of Bayoneta not to reach the merge.
Ruth-Marie was the oldest female contestant on Survivor: Panama.
Ruth-Marie is the first female contestant to use a dash in their name, followed by Peih-Gee Law of Survivor: China and Abi-Maria Gomes of Survivor: Philippines.
Ruth-Marie only voted against women.
The first Tribal Council Ruth-Marie attended was the only one at which she didn't receive votes.
Ruth-Marie is dubbed as 'RuMa' by the fans, after a fan video was made of her participating in Battle Dig where she raced Bobby to the finish mat.
Ruth-Marie is the only original member of Casaya to ever be a member of La Mina.
Bobby was the oldest member of Viveros.
Oddly, Bobby, who was assigned to a tribe of "younger men" shared the same age as Melinda, who was assigned to a tribe of "older women". Both were 32 at the time of filming.
Bobby was the first male voted out of Survivor: Panama.
Bobby is the first male who was voted out by a plurality (i.e. less than half of the total counted votes).
Bobby was the only original Viveros member to not make the merge.
Dan was the only original La Mina member to not make the merge.
Upon him being voted out of the game, his former tribemates saluted him.
Dan is the first and only castaway that has been an astronaut.
Nick holds the record for the fewest days played among contestants who reached the merge, with 18, tied with Julie McGee from Survivor: San Juan del Sur.
Nick was the last person to be voted out post-merge and not be on the jury until Corinne Kaplan in Survivor: Caramoan.
Austin was the first male to have a confessional in Survivor: Panama.
Austin was the only original Viveros member to be a juror in Panama.
Although it was not aired, Austin was the first contestant to create a fake Hidden Immunity Idol.
Sally's luxury item was a journal.
Sally is the first contestant to be abstained from Tribal Council due to being on Exile Island.
Bruce is the oldest castaway from Survivor: Panama.
Bruce's luxury item was a sketch pad.
Bruce is the first male castaway to sent to Exile Island.

Bruce is the first castaway to be exiled immediately after an odd-numbered tribe switch. He was followed by Lisi Linares in Fiji, Sugar Kiper in Gabon, Julia Sokolowski in Kaôh Rōng, Debbie Wanner in Game Changers, and Carl Boudreaux in David vs. Goliath.
Bruce went the longest without attending Tribal Council in Panama.

Bruce is the first Asian-American male to make it to the merge and subsequently the jury.
However, Bruce is the first Asian-American to do so on his first try. Shii Ann Huang was the first overall but did so on her second attempt (All-Stars).

Bruce became the second contestant to be evacuated for medical reasons, following Michael Skupin from Survivor: The Australian Outback. Unlike Michael, Bruce became the first contestant to be medically evacuated and become a member of the jury.
Bruce was the first contestant to be evacuated from a merged tribe, and also during the jury phase.
When they returned for Survivor: Heroes vs. Villains, both Danielle DiLorenzo and Sugar Kiper listed Bruce as the castaway they most respected in their profiles.
Courtney is the oldest member from the original Bayoneta tribe.
Courtney's luxury item was her fire dancing poi.
Courtney holds the record for being most recurring answer in the Q and A challenge, with 4.

Sekou was the oldest contestant on Survivor: Cook Islands.
Sekou is the first contestant in their forties to be the oldest contestant of a season. He was followed by Chicken Morris in China, Trish Hegarty in Cagayan, Katrina Radke in Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers, and Angela Perkins in Ghost Island.
Sekou is the first person to be voted out in 20th Place.
Sekou is the only contestant from Cook Islands to never be a member of either Rarotonga or Aitutaki.

Sekou is the first African-American contestant to be the first person eliminated from a season.
He would be followed by Francesca Hogi, Semhar Tadesse, and Darnell Hamilton.
Jolanda Jones was the first contestant to be voted out in Survivor: Palau, but she was not the first eliminated due to the Schoolyard Pick twist where Wanda Shirk and Jonathan Libby were eliminated.
At the Cook Islands Reunion Show, Sekou performed a song he wrote about Survivor.
Billy is the oldest member of the original Aitutaki tribe.
Billy was nominated for the "Best second boot" in Survivor Oz's The Ozcars.
According to his Reddit AMA, Billy auditioned at an open casting call and got in on the first try.
Cecilia was the first female to be voted out in Survivor: Cook Islands.
Cecilia is the lowest placing woman from the Aitutaki tribe.
Cecilia was the first person voted out after the tribe absorption.

She is the highest ranking castaway of Cook Islands to only be affiliated with one tribe.
She is the lowest ranking castaway to be the highest ranking contestant of a season to only be affiliated with one tribe.
Cecilia is the second contestant of Peruvian descent, following Kel Gleason and preceding Jay Starrett.
Cecilia is the only castaway from Survivor: Cook Islands to stay on the same tribe at the switch and be voted out pre-merge.
J.P. is the first LGBT Hispanic-American contestant to appear on Survivor.
Stephannie was the oldest female member of the Manihiki tribe.

Stephannie is the lowest placing female member of the Manihiki tribe.
She was also the first woman to be voted out of the Rarotonga tribe.
Stephannie has the most votes of all of the women in Cook Islands with 9 votes. Only Jonathan Penner has more votes than her.
Cao Boi was the oldest member of Puka Puka.
Cao Boi is the only member of Puka Puka to not make the jury phase of the game. Brad and Jenny were on the jury, while Yul and Becky made it to the Final Three.
Cristina was the oldest female from the original Aitutaki tribe.
Cristina was the last original member of Aitutaki to be voted out, due to Ozzy making it to Final Tribal Council.
Starting with Cristina, every person who was a member of Rarotonga at one point would be eliminated consecutively until none were left.

Jenny Guzon-Bae drew criticism for doodling a shooting gun on her vote for Cristina, a police officer who had been shot in the line of duty, on Night 15. Jenny later defended herself on Reunion Show, stating that she meant no ill will and had been putting drawings on everyone's votes.
Jessica was the first member from the original Rarotonga to be voted out.

Jessica was also the only member of the original Rarotonga to not make the merge.
