Out of the four people who were the first person voted out of their original tribes, Jessica was the only one who was female and the only one who wasn't the oldest member of their respective tribe.
Brad is the first LGBT Asian-American contestant to appear on Survivor. He would be followed by Tai Trang.
Brad is the first contestant to place 12th and be a member of the jury.
Brad is the second juror to not make the merge, after Erin Collins of Survivor: Thailand.
Brad is the first contestant to become a member of a nine-person jury.
Brad is the first juror to attend a pre-merge Tribal Council as a member of the jury.

Rebecca worked as a makeup artist for Survivor: The Australian Outback's Elisabeth Hasselbeck, who use to host The View from 2001-2013. Rebecca kept her Survivor stint a secret to avoid legal problems with television network ABC (which airs The View). When Rebecca revealed to Hasselbeck that she competed, Rebecca claimed that Elisabeth "was literally floored."
Rebecca, along with Jenny Guzon-Bae, are the first two castaways to be voted out by the same tribe at the same Tribal Council.
Rebecca is the first contestant to place 11th and be a member of the jury.

Rebecca was the second juror to not be on the same tribe as the eventual finalists, the first being Erin Collins.
Rebecca had the fewest interaction of any juror with finalists in Survivor history. Rebecca was on separate tribes with the Final Three and was voted out before the merge. The only time she interacted with one of the finalists before Final Tribal Council was when Ozzy Lusth accidentally discovered the Rarotonga camp.
Jenny was the oldest female contestant on Survivor: Cook Islands.

Jenny received harsh criticism from viewers of the show when she drew a gun on her parchment when voting for Cristina, as she had been wounded in the line of duty. Jenny later apologized at the Cook Islands Reunion Show, stating she never intended to offend anyone.
Jenny, along with Rebecca Borman, are the first two contestants to be voted out by the same tribe at the same Tribal Council.
Jenny was the first castaway to finish in 10th place and become a member of the jury.
Nate was the youngest member of the Manihiki tribe.

Nate holds the record for becoming the highest-ranking member of a certain gender of a tribe in the quickest time, doing so in three days. This was due to being one of two men on his tribe and the other one being voted out.
Nate only voted with the majority in unanimous votes.
Nate is one of 3 members of Aitutonga, along with Parvati Shallow and Adam Gentry, to have never been a member of Aitutaki.
Due to the early jury forming, Nate is the first player to finish 9th and not be the 1st member of the jury. Instead, he was the 4th.
Nate is the half-brother of Sal Masekela. Masekela was the presenter for The Daily 10, an entertainment program that formerly aired on the cable channel E!
Despite also being of Hispanic background, Nate was placed on the all African-American Manihiki tribe.
Adam was the only player in Cook Islands besides Ozzy to win individual immunity.
Adam was also the only Rarotonga member to win individual immunity.
Adam is the first player to be the 8th member of the jury on a season due to the Cook Islands early jury phase.
He is the first player to come in fifth place and be part of the finale episode of the season.

Adam was the highest-ranking contestant on Cook Islands to not receive a vote against them at his first Tribal Council on a certain tribe.
Sundra Oakley and Ozzy Lusth both received votes at their first Tribal Councils attended with their initial tribes.
Becky Lee received votes at her first Tribal Council attended with her post-absorption tribe.
Yul Kwon received votes at his first Tribal Council attended with the merge tribe.
Sundra was the only original Manihiki member to go over to the new Aitutaki after the tribe absorption in Survivor: Cook Islands.
Sundra was the youngest female of Manihiki.
Sundra was the highest placing member of Manihiki.
Sundra is the only member of the post-mutiny Aitutaki to be eliminated.

Whenever Sundra received votes at Tribal Council, she received exactly two.
Coincidentally enough, the two votes that Sundra receives are from people who were on an original tribe together.

Sundra was the first castaway to became the ninth member of the jury.
Additionally, she was the first person to place 4th and become the final member of the jury.
She was the only member of the Aitu Four alliance to be a member of the jury and the only post-mutiny member of Aitutaki to be on the jury. The other 8 jury members were from post-mutiny Rarotonga.
Becky was the youngest member of the original Puka Puka tribe.

Becky was the first Asian-American woman to make it to the merge and the jury phase on her first attempt. Shii Ann Huang made the merge and the jury on All-Stars, but was voted out pre-merge on her first attempt in Thailand.
Becky is the only member of the Cook Islands final seven to not reside in California at the time of filming.
Whenever Becky received a vote against her at Tribal Council, Ozzy Lusth and Sundra Oakley's were 2 of them.
In every Tribal Council Becky attended, whoever she voted for was the person who was eliminated.
Becky and Sundra Oakley hold the record for the longest time taken to complete a fire-making tiebreaker challenge, with one and a half hours.
Yul Kwon and Becky are the first and second Asian-Americans to reach the Final Tribal Council respectively.
Becky is the first castaway ever to make it to the Final Tribal Council and finish in 3rd place and the very first second runner-up in the show's history.
Becky is the first finalist to receive no jury votes.
Becky is the first female survivor contestant from Washington D.C.

Yul was the only person in Survivor: Cook Islands to be exiled and not be a member of the original Rarotonga tribe.
He was also the only person to be exiled once as the others sent to Exile Island were exiled at least three times each.
Yul is the first castaway to find the Hidden Immunity Idol and win the game.

Yul is the first and only Survivor contestant to reach Day 39 without ever being in danger of being voted out. Yul's original tribe won the two Immunity Challenges it competed in, after which Yul found the Hidden Immunity Idol, which he held until Day 38. This record is unlikely to be repeated due to the format change of the idol's usage the following season.
Yul is the first contestant to secure a seat at the Final Tribal Council before Day 38 - because of the aforementioned circumstances, following Adam's elimination at Tribal Council on Day 37, Yul was guaranteed to be in the finals as long as he did not relinquish his Hidden Immunity Idol.
Yul is the first Asian-American to reach the Final Tribal Council. He was immediately followed by Becky Lee, who won a tiebreaker on Day 38.
Yul was the first man to reach the Final Tribal Council without winning an individual Immunity Challenge, and subsequently the first man to win in such circumstances.
Yul is the first Sole Survivor to have the same number of votes against as the amount of jury votes for.
Yul is the first Sole Survivor to win against two finalists, as he was in the first Final Three in the show's history.
Yul is the first Asian-American Sole Survivor. He was followed by Natalie Anderson.

Jessica wasn't part of the official Ravu tribe picture, even though she was an official member of Ravu, because it was taken after Jessica was eliminated and Sylvia Kwan became part of Ravu due to the Survivor: Fiji Schoolyard Pick twist.
Jessica is the only Caucasian-American female contestant on Survivor: Fiji, as the other one that had been recruited dropped out before the season started.
Jessica is the only person to be voted off first and place 19th.
Sylvia was the oldest female in Survivor: Fiji.

Sylvia holds the record for the longest time without a tribe affiliation. Joining Ravu after they lost the first challenge, she became an official member only at their next challenge.
She is also the only castaway in Survivor to only be given their first tribe affiliation after someone with a tribe affiliation had been eliminated.
Sylvia was the first contestant voted out as the result of a split vote strategy.

Both times she went to Tribal Council, she received votes.
Anthony Robinson voted against her during those times.
Gary was the only Fiji contestant to apply for the show, as the other contestants, including Mellisa McNulty, were recruited.
Gary is the first contestant from Minnesota.
Gary is the oldest contestant on Survivor: Fiji.

Before the tribes were assigned, the 19 castaways had selected Gary himself and Sylvia as the people who were seen as leaders. Jeff then gave the two a bag and the person who picked the white rock would assign the tribes.
Gary is the first contestant to quit the game due to a medical reason. He was later followed by Dana Lambert in Survivor: Philippines, and Bi Nguyen in Survivor: David vs. Goliath.
Gary is one of six contestants to never attend Tribal Council, along with Jonathan Libby, Wanda Shirk, Kourtney Moon, Dana Lambert, and Pat Cusack.

Liliana was the only person voted out of Moto.
Liliana is the fourth contestant to be the only person voted out of their tribe before the jury phase, following Gabriel Cade, Willard Smith, and Sekou Bunch.
As revealed in the Reunion Show, Liliana gained 20 lbs. in preparation for competing.
Liliana is the first person to be voted out despite her tribe winning tribal immunity. This was due to a twist in the game. She would be followed by Bill Posley.
Rita's brother Nick Verreos appeared on the second season of Project Runway.
Rita is the oldest Hispanic contestant on Survivor: Fiji.
Rita is the only person who voted against Earl Cole, which prevented him from achieving the first "Perfect Game" in Survivor history.
Rita was the only Hispanic-American contestant on the original Ravu tribe.

Anthony was the first male contestant voted out from Survivor: Fiji, though not the first to be eliminated.
He was the only male to be voted out in Fiji and not be on the jury.
Anthony lasted the most days of all contestants who were eliminated without winning a challenge, lasting 16 days.
Anthony is the first contestant to be voted out on Day 16.
Anthony received the most votes in Survivor: Fiji, with 10 votes cast against him.
Rocky was one of two members of the jury who were never on the Moto tribe. The other was Mookie Lee.
He is nicknamed Rocky because of his striking resemblance to actor Sylvester Stallone.
Lisi was the only female member of the post-switch Ravu tribe.
Lisi is the only castaway from Fiji to switch tribes and be voted out pre-merge.
Lisi is the only castaway who was exiled after a Tribe Switch and later be voted out pre-merge.
Michelle was the youngest contestant in Fiji.
Michelle was the only Asian-American contestant to compete on Survivor: Fiji who was born in the United States.
Michelle was the only member of Ravu to not receive a vote prior to the merge.
Michelle was the only female member of the original Ravu to make the jury and the merge.
Edgardo is the lowest placing male member of the Bula Bula tribe.
Edgardo is the first male member of Moto to be voted out, as Gary Stritesky quit.
Mookie was the youngest male castaway on the Ravu tribe.
Among the Bula Bula tribe, Mookie was the only castaway to stay on Ravu throughout the pre-merge stage of the game, having never experienced the luxuries of the Moto camp.

Mookie was the first Survivor contestant to reach the merge without winning any Immunity Challenges. Ravu was immune from one Tribal Council, but by the other tribe giving up immunity after winning the challenge. He was followed by Denise Stapley in Philippines.
Mookie is the first person to give a Hidden Immunity Idol to another contestant.

Alex is the first person to play a Hidden Immunity Idol under the current format, before the votes are read.
Alex is the first person to play a Hidden Immunity Idol under the current format and not negate any votes against himself.
Stacy was the only Asian-American contestant on the original Moto tribe.
Stacy was the only female contestant in Fiji to win individual immunity
Stacy is the first person to be voted out of Survivor as a direct result of the Hidden Immunity Idol.
Stacy currently holds the record for most challenges (combined Reward Challenges, individual, and tribal immunity) won by a female contestant in a single season, with 15.
Boo is the first castaway to win a Reward Challenge that awarded him an advantage for the next Immunity Challenge.
Boo is the only Caucasian-American contestant to make it to the merge in Survivor: Fiji.
Boo is tied with Tom Westman (in Palau) for most challenges won in a single season, with 17.
Cassandra was the oldest female of Moto and of Bula Bula, and was the oldest African-American contestant on Fiji.
Cassandra is the second of five African-American women to reach the Final Tribal Council of Survivor after Vecepia Towery. They were followed by Sabrina Thompson, Tasha Fox, and Laurel Johnson.

Cassandra and Dreamz Herd are the first of six pairs to tie for the runner-up spot at the Final Tribal Council. The others are Lisa Whelchel and Michael Skupin from Philippines, Sherri Biethman and Dawn Meehan from Caramoan, Carolyn Rivera and Will Sims II from Worlds Apart, Spencer Bledsoe and Tasha Fox from Survivor: Cambodia, and Hannah Shapiro and Ken McNickle from Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
By virtue of being both runners-up, both Cassandra and Dreamz were awarded $100,000.

Dreamz is the last victim of the infamous Survivor Car Curse. Even though Dreamz did not win the Reward Challenge, Yau-Man Chan gave Dreamz the 2008 Ford Super Duty truck that he won. In return, Yau-Man asked Dreamz to give him the final four Individual Immunity Necklace should he win it. The curse would affect both men as Yau-Man finished 4th and Dreamz was the joint runner-up of Survivor: Fiji.
By virtue of winning the Final Immunity Challenge in Fiji, Dreamz is the first African-American male to make it to Day 39 and the Final Tribal Council.
Dreamz is the first male contestant to receive no jury votes at the Final Tribal Council.

Dreamz, along with Cassandra Franklin, were the first pair of castaways to be tied in second place. They would be followed by Michael Skupin and Lisa Whelchel from Survivor: Philippines, Dawn Meehan and Sherri Biethman from Survivor: Caramoan, Carolyn Rivera and Will Sims II from Survivor: Worlds Apart, Spencer Bledsoe and Tasha Fox from Survivor: Cambodia, and Hannah Shapiro and Ken McNickle from Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
By virtue of being both runners-up, both Dreamz and Cassandra were each awarded $100,000.
Earl never saw Survivor and hardly knew what it was when he was recruited to be on Fiji, only two days prior to filming.
Earl is the first person to play a Hidden Immunity Idol "by default" at the last time idols could be played.
Earl is the first player to play a Hidden Immunity Idol and ultimately win the season.

Earl is the first African-American male to win the title of Sole Survivor and the second African-American overall, following Vecepia Towery, who won Marquesas.
They would be followed by Jeremy Collins in Cambodia and Wendell Holland in Ghost Island.

Earl is the Sole Survivor to receive every jury vote. He was followed by J.T. Thomas in Tocantins, John Cochran in Caramoan, Jeremy Collins in Cambodia, and Adam Klein in Millennials vs. Gen X.
Earl is the first person to receive more than six jury votes.
At the Fiji Reunion Show, host Jeff Probst mistakenly stated that Earl never received a vote. In fact, he had received a single vote from Rita Verreos in "This Is Not Survival... It's a Thrival".
Earl was asked to compete on The Amazing Race with his eventual wife, Shelley. However, Shelley did not want to compete.
Chicken got his nickname from his occupation, a chicken farmer.
Chicken was the oldest contestant on Survivor: China.
Chicken had the first confessional in China.
Chicken is the first contestant with a nickname to have that nickname accompany his episode introductory screenshot.
Survivor columnist Mario Lanza of the Funny 115 named Chicken's outburst as the 8th funniest moment of Survivor seasons 12-20.

Ashley is the second castaway to receive votes from all of their original tribemates but not be voted out at their first Tribal Council, following Shii Ann Huang.
They were later followed by Gillian Larson, J'Tia Taylor, Alecia Holden, and Patrick Bolton.
Ashley is tied with Peih-Gee Law for the most votes cast against a female in Survivor: China, with 8.
Leslie is the only castaway to not finish the Buddhist ceremony on Day 1 of Survivor: China.
Leslie claimed to have applied 11 times before being cast for Survivor.
Leslie was the only member of Fei Long to be kidnapped.
Leslie's favorite season is Survivor: The Australian Outback.
Dave only voted against women at the Tribal Councils he attended.
Aaron was recruited to compete on Survivor and had seen Borneo, The Australian Outback, and Pearl Islands.
Aaron is the lowest-placing male member of the Fei Long tribe.
Sherea is the only female to switch tribes in Survivor: China.
Sherea was the only person to be voted out of Fei Long after the tribe switch, as well as being the only female to be voted out after the switch.
Jaime was the youngest woman to compete on Survivor: China.
Jaime was in the casting finals of Pirate Master before applying for Survivor.
Jaime is the first player in Survivor history to play an item mistakenly believed to be a Hidden Immunity Idol.
Jaime was the first woman to be the first member of the jury since Erin Collins in Survivor: Thailand.
Jean-Robert received the most votes out of everyone in Survivor: China, with 12, and had received votes every time he went to Tribal Council.

Frosti is the youngest contestant on Survivor: China.
Frosti is the first contestant under the age of 21 years to compete on Survivor.
Frosti and James Clement are the only castaways of Survivor: China to reach the merged tribe and participate in a Tribe Switch.
Erik is the only male castaway to make the merge in China and never be a member of Fei Long.
Erik was the only original Zhan Hu member who didn't vote for Todd Herzog at the Final Tribal Council.

Erik is the first jury member to vote for the Second Runner-Up at any Final Tribal Council in the show's history. He would be followed by Baylor Wilson of Survivor: San Juan del Sur and Devon Pinto of Survivor: Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.

Erik and Jaime Dugan are the first pair of Survivor contestants from the same original season to marry each other. Rob Mariano and Amber Brkich both competed on Survivor: All-Stars, but were from different original seasons.
Denise is the oldest member of Fei Long and the oldest woman to compete on China.
Denise auditioned at an open casting call and had applied for Survivor: Fiji and Pirate Master before getting cast for China.
Denise is the last juror not to have a Ponderosa.
Denise was the only female from the original Fei Long tribe to be on the jury.
Todd is the youngest member of Fei Long.
Todd applied for Cook Islands and Fiji before getting accepted to be on Survivor: China.
He and Amanda Kimmel voted for the same person at every Tribal Council they attended.
Todd is the second LGBT contestant to make it to Final Tribal Council, following Richard Hatch, from Survivor: Borneo. They were followed by Tai Trang in Survivor: Kaôh Rōng.
Todd is the first winner to defeat two finalists who were both of the same gender at the Final Tribal Council.
Also having a Canadian citizenship, Todd is the second contestant with dual citizenship to compete on Survivor, following fellow winner Aras Baskauskas.
In her introduction video, Mary said her favorite castaways were Stephenie LaGrossa and Parvati Shallow.
He voted for Chet Welch at both Tribal Councils he attended.
Joel auditioned for Survivor at an opening casting call in Arizona.
The final vote cast for Joel that eliminated him read "Truck".
Chet was the oldest member of the original Airai tribe.
Chet received votes against him at every Tribal Council he attended.

Chet asked his tribemates to vote him out. It is speculated that this was because he was soon going to be medically evacuated due to having a piece of coral lodged in his foot, which Chet claimed happened during the Day 7 Reward Challenge, and that if he had not been voted out, Malakal would have lost two members.
Chet received the most votes against him out of any contestant in Micronesia, with 12.
Kathy Sleckman stated that Chet was recruited to compete on Survivor.
Kathy was in the shortlist of 50 applicants for Survivor: Vanuatu. Kathy sent five audition tapes prior to Survivor: Micronesia.
Kathy was the oldest female to compete on Micronesia.
Kathy was the first castaway to win individual immunity but not use it for the immediate Tribal Council.
Kathy was the only original Airai member to not receive any votes against them.
Kathy is the only castaway on Micronesia to stay on Airai during the tribe switch and be eliminated pre-merge.

Tracy was the last member of the original Airai tribe to be voted out before the merge.
She was, however, the first female to be voted out of Malakal.
Tracy applied for Survivor at an open casting call.
Jason auditioned for Survivor at an open casting call near Chicago.

Jason is the eighth player to find a Hidden Immunity Idol.
Jason is the third player to be blindsided while in the possession of a Hidden Immunity Idol, following James Clement and Ozzy Lusth.
Jason is the older brother of Adam Siska, the former bassist of The Academy Is... and current bassist for Say Anything.
Both times Jason received votes at Tribal Council, he received exactly 4 votes.
Jason is the only male on the Micronesia jury to vote for Parvati Shallow.
Jason is the first castaway to be originally from the U.S. Virgin Islands.
Alexis was the youngest female member of the original Airai tribe.
Alexis is the only member of the Black Widow Brigade to be outlasted by a male.
Alexis lost 20 lbs. during her time in Micronesia.

occupation:
Ice Cream Scooper;
Comic Book Artist

trivia: In a pre-game video, Natalie said her favorite past character was Ozzy Lusth.
Natalie is the highest ranking member of the Fans on Survivor: Micronesia.
Natalie is currently the only contestant from Micronesia's final five that has not returned for another season.
Natalie lost 18 lbs. during her time in Micronesia.
Natalie was an alternate for Survivor: Heroes vs. Villains, but was cut the day before filming began.

Due to the extended 2 hour premiere episode, her final words and all the votes from that Tribal Council that are normally at the end of the episode were cut out. However, it was made available for viewers to watch on the CBS website after the episode was aired.
Michelle is the youngest female of the Fang tribe.
Gillian is the oldest contestant on Gabon.

Gillian is the third castaway to receive votes from all of their original tribemates, but not be voted out at their first Tribal Council, following Shii Ann Huang and Ashley Massaro.
They were later followed by J'Tia Taylor, Alecia Holden, and Patrick Bolton.
Gillian is one of only two females to play Survivor while being over 60 years old, following Sonja Christopher from Borneo.
Gillian auditioned for the show for eight years before being cast to compete on Gabon.
Paloma was the only female voted out of Kota.

Paloma was the only female in Gabon to never be a member of the Fang tribe.
Furthermore, she is the only castaway Crystal Cox and Ken Hoang were never on a tribe with.
Paloma was the lowest-placing member of Kota.
While Jacquie was on Survivor, she and producer Tyler Ramsey had a fling, causing his firing as the one rule for producers is "Never mess with the contestants". The two later married.
His nickname, G.C., stands for "Golden Child". He was also referred to as G. Cizzle.
G.C. was the first male contestant voted out from Survivor: Gabon, after four Tribal Councils in which women were voted out.
G.C. was the only original Fang member to stay on Fang after the tribal switch and be voted out from the tribe.
Kelly is the youngest contestant on Survivor: Gabon.
Every person Kelly voted for, voted for her.
Ace is the youngest male contestant on the original Kota tribe.
Ace is the first (and so far) only English contestant to compete on Survivor.
Ace was cast for Survivor: Heroes vs. Villains, but was allegedly cut three days before filming.
Dan is the only person from Gabon to be sent to Exile Island and not make the Final Tribal Council.

Marcus is the first contestant to reach the jury phase without ever being vulnerable at a pre-jury Tribal Council.
This feat was replicated by the entire original Tandang tribe in Philippines, Joe Anglim and Keith Nale in Cambodia, Michele Fitzgerald and Nick Maiorano in Kaôh Rōng, Cirie Fields in Game Changers, Cole Medders, Jessica Johnston, and Mike Zahalsky in Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers, and Chris Noble in Ghost Island.
He is the only contestant to achieve this yet not reach the merge.

Marcus held the record for the most consecutive days starting from Day 1 without being vulnerable at Tribal Council. First being vulnerable on Day 24, he was eliminated the first time he was vulnerable.
Marcus' immunity streak record was broken by Joe Anglim during Cambodia, who was immune for the first 29 days of the game. Because Joe was a returning contestant, Marcus still holds the record for a first-timer.
Marcus is one of two original Kotas (along with Bob Crowley) to remain on Kota after both tribe switches.
Marcus is the first contestant to win individual immunity twice in a single season and not make the merge. Gabon was the first season in which this was possible.
Marcus holds the record for the longest time between winning immunity and using said immunity. He won immunity on Day 1, and then used it on Day 9, when Kota went to their first Tribal Council.
Marcus lost 15 lbs. during his time in Gabon.
Charlie lost 13-14 lbs. during his time in Gabon.
Crystal is the tallest woman to play Survivor so far, at 6'3" (190 cm).
Crystal lost 22 lbs. during her time in Survivor: Gabon.
Crystal had the first confessional in Gabon.

Crystal won 2 challenges and lost 19 over the course of the game. Of the 19 losses, 11 were tribal challenges, and 8 were individual challenges.
Both challenges Crystal won were in the same episode.
Crystal's 11 losses in tribal challenges tie her with Bobby Jon Drinkard, Stephenie LaGrossa, and her tribemate Ken Hoang for the second-most in a single season. The person with the most losses in tribal challenges is Mookie Lee with 12.
Crystal was only immune for one Tribal Council.
Crystal, along with her tribemate Ken, was on a tribe with every castaway in her season at some point, with the exception of Paloma Soto-Castillo.
Crystal had the most votes cast against her in Survivor: Gabon with 11.
Crystal applied for Survivor at an open casting call in Virginia.
Ken is the youngest male in Survivor: Gabon (at 22) and the youngest on the original Fang.
Ken is the one who came up with the idea of naming the merged tribe "Nobag" - Gabon spelled backward.
Ken is the only person in Gabon to win an individual challenge after the merge but not be a finalist.
Ken, along with his tribemate Crystal Cox, was on a tribe with every castaway in her season at some point, with the exception of Paloma Soto-Castillo.
Ken lost 20 lbs. during his time in Gabon.
Matty is the grandson of actor James Whitmore.

Matty was the only original Fang member to remain on Fang during both tribe shuffles.
As such, Matty is the only member of Nobag to never be on Kota.

Matty proposed to his long-term girlfriend, which she accepted, while in Gabon during the Loved Ones visit. He carved a ring out of wood and put it on a necklace, which he put around her neck when she accepted. She was wearing the necklace at the Reunion Show.
Matty lost about 17 lbs. during his time on Gabon.
Matty was recruited to compete on Survivor when he met a casting agent at a Whole Foods Market with his girlfriend in Santa Monica. Before being cast, Matty had rarely watched Survivor.

Susie is the only female to win individual immunity in Gabon.
However, Sugar Kiper was given individual immunity from Marcus Lehman in "It All Depends on the Pin-Up Girl".
Susie gained her three jury votes from the members of the Fang Alliance which she was a part of.
Susie is the first female contestant from Iowa.
Susie was the highest placing member of the Fang tribe.

Susie is the first person in Survivor history to be on a tribe and never give a confessional as a member.
Susie didn't make her first confessional until the first tribe switch, when she went to Kota.
Susie was, however, shown giving a confessional during her time on the Fang tribe during the recap episode.

Susie is currently one of three contestants (along with Ozzy Lusth in Cook Islands and Michele Fitzgerald in Kaôh Rōng) to win the Final Immunity Challenge and vote for someone who didn't get voted out.
Survivor: Vanuatu contestant Julie Berry attended Bob's high school in Maine and took his class as a student.
Bob introduced the bowtie as a way of wearing a buff. So far, he is the only one to sport this style.

When Randy played Bob's fake Hidden Immunity Idol, Jeff threw it into the fire (as is usual practice), much to the dislike of the viewers. However, once the Tribal Council was over, Jeff pulled it out so he could give it back to Bob at the Reunion Show.

Bob is one of three winners to be involved in a tie vote at some point in the game, the others being Richard Hatch and Natalie White.
He, along with Ben Driebergen and Wendell Holland, are the only three people to win the fire making tiebreaker and become the Sole Survivor. Bob is the only person to win it as a tiebreaker, as the other two winners played under the modified final four format introduced in Survivor: Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Bob is currently the oldest Survivor winner. Bob was 57 years, 9 months and 20 days old when he was declared the Sole Survivor.

Bob was the first Sole Survivor to also win the Fan Favorite Award. He was followed by J.T. Thomas, Rob Mariano, and Kim Spradlin.
Bob is the only male Fan Favorite to compete only once.
On Rob Has a Podcast, Bob revealed that he was actually an alternate for Gabon and replaced eventual Survivor: Nicaragua castaway Jimmy Johnson when the latter failed his medical exam.
Carolina is the first Hispanic-American to be the first person voted out of a season.

Carolina was a last minute replacement for this season. Her original spot was to be filled by Survivor: Philippines and Survivor: Cambodia castaway Abi-Maria Gomes, but the producers felt Abi-Maria would have an edge due to her living close to the Tocantins.
Candace is the second Miss Ohio USA winner to compete on Survivor, after Kim Mullen of Palau.
In 2004, Candace appeared as a model on The Price Is Right.
Jerry is the oldest contestant on Timbira, as well as the oldest male contestant on Tocantins.
During her appearance in Tocantins, Sandy constantly mispronounced "Jalapao" as "Jalapeño."
Sandy is the oldest contestant of Jalapao and of Tocantins.
Sandy received at least one vote at every Tribal Council she attended.
Spencer is the first teenager to compete on Survivor and had long been the youngest castaway at the time of filming until Will Wahl was cast for Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.

Spencer is the only male Jalapao member to be voted out. Joe Dowdle was medically evacuated and Stephen Fishbach and J.T. Thomas were the Final Two.
He is also the only male Jalapao member to not make it to the merge.
During her time on Tocantins, Sydney commonly wore tribemate J.T.'s boxers as shorts, as she only had a pair of jeans, which weren't comfortable when the weather was hot.
Sydney lost 13 lbs. (5 kg) during her time in Tocantins.
Joe is the first contestant to be the lowest-placing member of a merged tribe due to a medical evacuation.

Joe is the first contestant to make the merge, but never attend a post-merge Tribal Council as a contestant.
He was followed by Julie McGee and Neal Gottlieb.
Joe is the third of six contestants to be evacuated after the merge, succeeding Bruce Kanegai and James Clement and preceding Erik Reichenbach, Neal Gottlieb, and Joe del Campo.
Joe is the only member of the Tocantins cast to not have their torch snuffed during any Survivor season, as the season's Final Two were voted out of later seasons.
Brendan is the "Dragon" who inspired his rival, Coach Wade, to become the "Dragon Slayer".
Brendan is the fourth person to be voted out with a Hidden Immunity Idol in his possession.
Brendan lost 6 lbs. during his time in Tocantins.
Coach Wade often referred to her as "The Dragon's Bride" as she was in an alliance with Brendan Synnott, who was "The Dragon".

Sierra is the youngest person on the Timbira tribe.
Sierra was also the youngest female on Tocantins.
She had the most votes against her in Tocantins with 11.
Sierra lost 11 lbs. during her time on Tocantins.
Debbie was the oldest female in the Timbira tribe.
Debbie was the oldest contestant on the merged tribe Forza in Survivor: Tocantins.
Debbie was the only female to win individual immunity in Tocantins.
Debbie lost 6 lbs. during her time in Tocantins.

Taj is one of four women to be married to an NFL player and appear on Survivor.
The others are Elisabeth Filarski, Danni Boatwright, and Monica Culpepper.
She is the first, however, to be married to an NFL player before appearing on Survivor.
Taj is the only contestant to vote against Joe Dowdle and only Jalapao member never to vote against Sandy Burgin.
Taj was the only woman from the Jalapao tribe to reach the merge on Tocantins.
Taj is the first African-American woman to find a Hidden Immunity Idol.

Taj is the only person from Jalapao to be voted out of Forza.
She is also the only Jalapao member to be part of the jury.
Taj lost 27 lbs. during her time in Tocantins.
Erinn had the first confessional of Survivor: Tocantins.
Erinn was the last original Timbira tribe member left in the game.
Erinn is the only contestant to write Stephen Fishbach's name on Tribal Council parchment in Tocantins.
Erinn lost 17 lbs. during her time in Tocantins.
Marisa is the only Foa Foa member who was voted out in a non-unanimous vote.
Mike was the oldest contestant to compete on Survivor: Samoa.

According to the host Jeff Probst's cast assessment, Mike was originally slated to appear on Survivor: Tocantins, but due to his health, was put on reserve until he improved. Mike also confirmed this in post-game interviews.
Betsy is the oldest female in Survivor: Samoa.

Ben is one of five people to be disqualified from a challenge.
However, because Ken Stafford, Robb Zbacnik, Stephanie Dill, and Jed Hildebrand in Thailand broke a specific rule, Ben is the first player to be arbitrarily ejected from a challenge at the sole judgement of host Jeff Probst.
Ben was the only male contestant to be voted out before the merge in Samoa, as both Mike Borassi and Russell Swan were evacuated.
Ben was recruited to play Survivor when he was discovered at a boardwalk in California.
Yasmin was the only original Galu member to be voted out pre-merge.
Yasmin was recruited to play on Survivor.
Yasmin has made various appearances on TV before her appearance on Survivor.
Ashley is the youngest contestant on Survivor: Samoa.
Ashley received votes against her in every Tribal Council she appeared in except for one.
Ashley originally applied for The Amazing Race with a friend before being asked to apply for Survivor.
Ashley was one of the two alternates added to compete in Samoa at the last minute. The other was Galu's Erik Cardona.
According to a post game interview, Liz was recruited to be on Survivor and hadn't watched the show since Survivor: The Australian Outback.
Erik was one of the two alternates added to compete in Samoa at the last minute. The other was Foa Foa's Ashley Trainer.
The original intro for Survivor: Samoa had Erik's name misspelled with a "C" instead of a "K".
Erik lost 17.6 lbs. during his time in Samoa.
He is tied with Laura Morett for the most votes cast against them in Samoa, with 10.
Kelly was the third person to be voted out as a direct result of an Hidden Immunity Idol being played.

Kelly is the only person from Aiga to receive votes from only all four former Foa Foa members post-merge.
Brett Clouser also received votes from only Foa Foa members, but Jaison Robinson was already eliminated at that point.
Kelly has the least amount of votes cast against a female in Survivor: Samoa, with 4.
Kelly lost 9 lbs. during her time in Samoa.

Kelly shares many similarities with Kelly Remington.
They're both named Kelly.
They were both blindsided from a Hidden Immunity Idol with 4 votes against them.
They both were the second lowest placing females of their original tribes, Galu and Escameca and were also the lowest placing females of their merged tribes, Aiga and Merica.

John is one of the seven jurors to cast a vote against all of the finalists in their season.
The other six are Shane Powers, Erik Reichenbach, Brett Clouser, Tasha Fox, Jeremiah Wood, and Spencer Bledsoe.
John lost 20.7 lbs. during his time in Samoa.
Jeff Probst always referred to Dave by his full name.
Dave was an alternate contestant for Survivor: China.
Dave lost 18 lbs. during his time in Samoa.
Shambo was offered a chance to return for Survivor: Caramoan and Survivor: Cambodia, but she declined on both occasions.
Erik Cardona referred to Jaison as "an enigma; he has all the tools that can make him a great player but he fails to use them".
Jaison is the youngest male on Foa Foa.

Jaison was the last member of the Foa Foa tribe to get voted off.
Jaison was also the only Foa Foa to be voted off after the merge.
Jaison was the only Foa Foa member on the jury.
Jaison lost 35 lbs. during his time in Survivor: Samoa.
Brett is the youngest member of Galu, as well as the youngest man in Samoa.
Brett had the first confessional of Samoa.
Brett is the only member of Galu to outlast a member of the Foa Foa Four.
Brett lost 30 lbs. during his time in Samoa.
According to his red carpet interview at the Reunion Show, Brett's favorite Survivor castaway is Rudy Boesch.
Mick is friends with Survivor: South Pacific contestant, Edna Ma. Edna solicited advice from Mick before heading to Samoa.

Mick and his fellow finalists, Natalie White and Russell Hantz, holds the record for the most Tribal Councils attended within a single season with 16 (including the Final Tribal Council and Tribal Council where Russell Swan was announced to be evacuated). However, if the latter is discounted, Denise Stapley, Spencer Bledsoe (in Cambodia), and Ken McNickle also share the record at 15.
Every time Mick received a vote, it came from the person he had voted for at that Tribal Council.
Whenever Mick received votes, he only had one cast against him.
Mick was recruited to play Survivor when he met a casting director while having dinner with a friend.
Natalie originally applied to appear on The Amazing Race with her boyfriend, but was transferred.

Natalie is the only female member of Foa Foa to make the merge.
She is also the only female member of Foa Foa to never receive a vote pre-merge.

Natalie was eligible to be voted out 14 times, the most for any castaway in a single season.
She ties with Denise Stapley, Ken McNickle, Mick Trimming, Russell Hantz (in Samoa), and Spencer Bledsoe (in Cambodia) for the most Tribal Councils attended, with 15 (including the Final Tribal Council), but she is the only one who was never immune, while the five others had individual immunity at least once.
Natalie is tied with Kim Spradlin and Sarah Lacina for the most jury votes for a woman, at 7.
Natalie is the only member of the Foa Foa Four to not win individual immunity.
Natalie has the least amount of challenge wins than any other Sole Survivor with three.
Natalie is the first woman to become the Sole Survivor in a season with a Final Three format
Natalie is the first female Sole Survivor to win a season comprised entirely of new castaways since Sandra Diaz-Twine in Survivor: Pearl Islands, 12 seasons prior.
Natalie is the third winner to be involved in a tie, following Richard Hatch and Bob Crowley.
Despite only receiving votes at one Tribal Council, Natalie has the most votes cast against her out of any other female Sole Survivor with 8 votes.
Natalie is the first castaway of two contestants named Natalie to win Survivor, the other being Natalie Anderson.
Coincidentally, Wendy's husband said that she would be the first one off, and she was.

It confused the audience when Wendy's vote was revealed to be for Yve Rojas, who was never in danger of leaving prior to the vote. In her voting confessional, Wendy revealed that she made an alliance with Yve, but Yve did not tell her that she would be targeted, which made her upset, thus explaining her vote for Yve.
Wendy was the only woman voted off before the tribe switch on Nicaragua.
Rob Cesternino referred to Wendy in one of his podcasts as "the worst contestant in the history of Survivor."
Wendy placed last in Survivor Oz's ranking of all players from Survivor: Borneo to Survivor: San Juan del Sur.
Shannon is the only male from the original La Flor to not make the merge.
Jimmy J. was supposed to be slated in Gabon, but he failed a medical test after doctors discovered two blocked arteries.
Jimmy J. was the oldest contestant on Nicaragua.

Jimmy J. was the second person in the history of the show who was affiliated with the NFL before doing Survivor. The first was Gary Hogeboom. He would later be followed by Steve Wright, Grant Mattos, Brad Culpepper, Tyler Fredrickson, and Alan Ball.
Jimmy Tarantino is the first castaway to not be selected in a conventional casting call or recruited by the casting producers.

In one of the Survivor: Nicaragua promos, Jimmy said that "America should have a pen and a note pad when they see him playing", but at the live Reunion Show, Jimmy later admits that he regretted saying that, likely because of his early exit.
Tyrone was the youngest male on the original Espada tribe.
Kelly B. is the second amputee Survivor contestant, following Chad Crittenden from Survivor: Vanuatu.
Kelly B. is the lowest-placing female member of the La Flor tribe.
Kelly B. was the first contestant to be voted out during a pre-merge tied vote since James Miller from Survivor: Palau.
Kelly B. is the only female member of the original La Flor to not be part of the merged tribe or the jury.
Both times Kelly B. attended Tribal Council, she voted against the oldest male on her tribe.
Yve was the youngest member of the original Espada tribe.
Jill was the only person from Nicaragua to switch tribes and be voted out pre-merge.

Alina was voted out in a Tribal Council that breached beyond the standard three-day cycle. The gap between Tribal Councils of "What Goes Around, Comes Around" and "Company Will Be Arriving Soon" was four days, the longest gap between two Tribal Councils in successive episodes in the history of the series. This would then be followed by the Tribal Councils in "Not Sure Where I Stand" and "This Is Going to Hurt".
Alina revealed that she let Kelly Shinn have her scarf after being voted out.
Alina revealed in a Survivor Oz interview she was asked to return for Survivor: South Pacific, but did not make the final cast.
Alina lost 8 lbs. during her time in Nicaragua.
It was Marty who came up with "Libertad" as the merged tribe name for Survivor: Nicaragua.
Jane voted for Marty five consecutive times at every tribal after the tribe switch, a Survivor record.
In Nicaragua, Marty had the most votes against him with 15 votes.
Marty was the 300th contestant voted out of Survivor.
Marty lost 22 lbs. during his time in Nicaragua.
NaOnka and Kelly Shinn became the first contestants to quit at the same Tribal Council.
NaOnka is the only castaway to find the Hidden Immunity Idol before quitting; she gave her idol to Chase Rice before leaving the game.
NaOnka cast a vote against all the eventual boots in every Tribal Council she had attended.

At the Day 28 Tribal Council, NaOnka erroneously noted that she was the last African-American left in the competition at the time, which was not the case since Sash Lenahan was still in (he is half African-American, as he even told NaOnka in the beginning of the game when forming an alliance with her).

At the Survivor: Nicaragua Reunion Show, Jeff Probst revealed that after Mixon and Shinn's simultaneous voluntary exits, the producers decided that, if a contestant quit the show, the producers would deliberate whether or not put the quitter on the jury. Jeff further revealed that the producers will reserve the right to withhold the quitter's consolation prize.
Had Mixon and Shinn not been permitted to join the jury and the same vote would have taken place, Chase Rice would have won the season in a 4-3-0 vote.
NaOnka had the most confessionals out of all of the Nicaragua contestants, with 50.
NaOnka lost 11 lbs. during her time in Nicaragua.

Kelly is the youngest contestant to compete on Survivor: Nicaragua.
She is the first contestant who was born in the 1990s.
Kelly's nickname comes from the purple highlights in her hair. This was done to properly distinguish her from Kelly Bruno.
Purple Kelly currently holds the record for the latest first confessional in the history of the show, which occurred in "What Goes Around, Comes Around", the seventh episode of the season.
Kelly is the highest ranking original La Flor female.
Kelly is the only contestant in Survivor: Nicaragua who did not receive a vote against them.

Purple Kelly and NaOnka Mixon are the first contestants to quit at the same Tribal Council.
Kelly is the youngest contestant to quit Survivor.
At the Survivor: Nicaragua Reunion Show, Jeff Probst revealed that after Purple Kelly and NaOnka's simultaneous voluntary exits, the producers decided that, if a contestant quit the show, the producers would deliberate whether or not put the quitter on the jury. Jeff further revealed that the producers will reserve the right to withhold the quitter's consolation prize.
Kelly lost 12 lbs. during her time in Nicaragua.
Benry's nickname is a portmanteau of his first and last name.
Upon arriving in Ponderosa, the medical staff was forced to see Benry's hand due to a large blister caused by a severe burn just days before. He lost 34.7 lbs.
Benry was the only original male La Flor member to be a part of the jury. Shannon Elkins was voted out pre-jury, and Fabio Birza, Chase Rice, and Sash Lenahan all reached the Final Tribal Council.
Jane is the oldest woman in Survivor: Nicaragua.
Jeff Probst did not include Jane in his assessment of the cast.
Including members before and after the swap, Jane is the only Espada member to win individual immunity after the merge. Holly and Jill won their individual immunity before the merge.
Jane cast five consecutive votes for Marty Piombo, a Survivor record.
Jane won the most Immunity Challenges out of all the female players in Survivor: Nicaragua, with two.
Jane lost 14.1 lbs. during her time in Nicaragua.
Jane is the first woman to win the Sprint Player of the Season award. This makes her the second woman to win the Fan Favorite Award, following Cirie Fields.

On the Reunion Show interview, Dan revealed that he was happy with how far he made it because he completed all 3 of his milestones he set for himself: not being the first one voted off, making the merge, and making the final 5.
Dan was the last remaining male from his original tribe.
Dan lost 25 lbs. during his time in Nicaragua.

Former winner Tina Wesson stated in Rob Has A Podcast that she rooted for Holly. Wesson also revealed that Holly and Chase's relationship reminded her of her relationship with Colby Donaldson back in Survivor: The Australian Outback.

Holly is the first, and currently only, Survivor contestant from South Dakota.
Mitchell Olson from Survivor: The Australian Outback was born in South Dakota, but did not live there at the time of filming.
In his cast assessment of Survivor: South Pacific, Jeff Probst revealed that Holly was chosen to compete at the last minute over Dawn Meehan.
Holly is the first castaway to sacrifice a reward to supply rice and a tarp for her merged tribe Libertad.
Holly was the highest ranking original member of the Espada tribe and the highest ranking woman on Nicaragua.
Holly lost 22 lbs. during her time in Nicaragua.
Holly revealed that she bought her own torch as a souvenir after the game ended.
Sash was the oldest member of the original La Flor tribe.
Sash is half-Caucasian, half-African.
According a pre-show interview, Lenahan's nickname, Sash, came from his inability to pronounce Matthew when he was 3 and he always had said Sashew.
During the pre-show interviews, host Jeff Probst predicted that Sash would be eliminated early in the game, but his perseverance earned Probst's respect.

At the Day 28 Tribal Council, NaOnka Mixon erroneously noted that she was the last African-American left in the competition at the time, which was not the case since Sash was still in (he is half African-American, as he even told NaOnka in the beginning of the game when forming an alliance with her).
If NaOnka Mixon and Kelly Shinn had not been permitted to join the jury, and the same vote had happened, Chase would have beaten Fabio in a 4-3-0 vote.

Chase became the first castaway to not be picked and miss out on the benefit of competing in the challenge. However, he was given the opportunity to choose the winning team, if he chose correctly he would get to go on the reward with them. He chose the team of women.
Chase voted correctly at every Tribal Council he attended.
Chase performed a sample of one of his singles at the Survivor: Nicaragua live Reunion Show.
He is tied with Ozzy Lusth for the most votes received by a Runner-Up with 4.
Chase is the first male to receive all of his jury votes from females.
Chase is the first male finalist to make it to Final Tribal Council without winning Individual Immunity but not become the Sole Survivor.
Fabio was the youngest male contestant on Survivor: Nicaragua.
Fabio had the first confessional in Nicaragua.
It was Shannon Elkins who nicknamed Jud to "Fabio," after Italian fashion model Fabio Lanzoni.
Fabio is the first person to have his name changed in the opening intro, where his name was changed from "Jud" in the first episode to "Fabio" in the second.
Fabio is the first person to win a Final Three where all of the finalists were of the same gender.

Fabio currently ties with Jenna Morasca for the record of youngest winner, with both being 21 during the time of filming. However, Jenna had turned 22 before being declared the Sole Survivor of Survivor: The Amazon. This makes Fabio the youngest winner when declared the Sole Survivor.
Kristina is the first woman to find the Hidden Immunity Idol without any clues.
She holds the record for the earliest use of the Hidden Immunity Idol, using it unsuccessfully on Day 5 of Redemption Island.
Kristina is tied with Sabrina Thompson and Carolyn Rivera for the second earliest discovery of a Hidden Immunity Idol by a woman, finding one on Day 2.
Kristina voted against Phillip Sheppard, and received a vote from Andrea Boehlke, at every Tribal Council she attended.
Kristina is the first contestant to be targeted by a split vote more than once.
Krista's luxury item was a Bible, which she gave to Matt Elrod.

Sarita is one of six female players (along with Laura Morett, Laura Boneham, Tina Wesson, Christine Shields Markoski, and Andrea Boehlke) to compete in the Final Duel on Redemption Island (either pre-merge or post-merge).
Sarita is the only member of the Zapatera Six to not make the merge.
Jeff Probst confirmed that David has the highest IQ of any Survivor contestant, at 144.
David is the first person to lose a Redemption Island duel and become a member of the jury.
David was the first new male contestant, and first male member of the Zapatera Six alliance, to be permanently eliminated from Survivor: Redemption Island.
David stated that he lost between 15 to 20 lbs. during his time on Redemption Island.

On Ponderosa, David said that if there was something he wished he had done differently, it would be to not make an alliance before getting to know your alliance mates, likely referring to his conflict with Sarita White.

David is the second contestant to propose on a live Reunion Show, following Rob Mariano, who proposed to Amber Brkich during the Survivor: All-Stars live show.
Both players competed in Survivor: Redemption Island.
Julie was the oldest woman on Survivor: Redemption Island.
Julie was the highest-placing female member of Zapatera, but the lowest-placing female member of Murlonio. This was possible because she was the only female member of Zapatera to make the merge.
Julie lost 24 lbs. during her time on Redemption Island.
Steve was the oldest member of Zapatera.

Steve's former NFL teammate Gary Hogeboom competed on Survivor: Guatemala, eleven seasons before Steve himself did so.
Steve is the third person in the history of the show who was affiliated with the NFL before doing Survivor, following Gary Hogeboom and Jimmy Johnson. He would later be followed by Brad Culpepper, Tyler Fredrickson, and Alan Ball.

Steve is the fifth-tallest contestant to compete at 6' 6" (201 cm), following Survivor: The Australian Outback contestant Mitchell Olson, who is 7 feet (213 cm) tall, Survivor: Kaôh Rōng contestant Scot Pollard who is 6'11 (210 cm), Survivor: Cagayan contestant Cliff Robinson who is 6'10 (208 cm), and Survivor: Palau contestant Ian Rosenberger who is 6'8 (207 cm).
Steve lost 33 lbs. during his time on Redemption Island.
Similar to Borneo and All-Stars contestant Susan Hawk, Ralph was also known for casting poorly-spelled votes (i.e. "Ressell", "Krasta", "Stifinie", and "Philite" at the Final Tribal Council).
Ralph is the oldest player to win a duel on Survivor: Redemption Island.
It was stated by Jeff Probst that Ralph was his favorite Castaway of Redemption Island.
Ralph was the only jury member to not vote for Rob Mariano for the title of Sole Survivor in Redemption Island.
Ralph lost 24 lbs. during his time on Redemption Island.
Grant was friends with Micronesia castaway Natalie Bolton, who was a big part of him auditioning for Survivor.

Grant is the fourth person in the history of the show who was affiliated with the NFL before doing Survivor, following Gary Hogeboom, Jimmy Johnson, and Steve Wright. He would later be followed by Brad Culpepper, Tyler Fredrickson, and Alan Ball.
Grant is one of the two former NFL players on Redemption Island, the other being Steve Wright.﻿
Matt was the youngest male contestant to compete on Survivor: Redemption Island.
Matt is the first person to be voted out on Day 5.
He is also the first male to be ever sent to Redemption Island.

Matt is the first contestant to return from Redemption Island.
He is also the first of three contestants to be sent to Redemption Island twice (the second one is Ozzy Lusth, with the third being Laura Morett).
After losing the duel to him, Krista lent to Matt her luxury item: a bible.

Though he did not win any challenges as part of Ometepe, he did win the most Redemption Island duels, winning ten of eleven. He also spent the most time on Redemption Island, spending there 29 days of his 36-day run.
He is the only contestant to reach the merge without winning a single tribal challenge.
However, Denise Stapley reached the merge with only 1 tribal challenge victory and that came via forfeit.
Matt was referenced in the Survivor: South Pacific episode "Reap What You Sow" by Christine Shields Markoski, who said "It would be great if I pulled a Matt and returned to the game."

Matt is the first of two contestants to return from Redemption Island, but eventually lose a duel - resulting in their elimination, with the other being Laura Morett. Andrea Boehlke, Ozzy Lusth, and Tina Wesson also returned from Redemption Island, but never lost a duel.
Matt is also the only person to participate in every single duel at Redemption Island.
Matt has the record for longest Redemption Island winning streak at 10 consecutive wins.
Matt lost 25 lbs. during his time on Redemption Island.
Matt turned down the offer to appear for a second time in Survivor: Caramoan as a favorite.
Mike is the youngest male member of Zapatera.
Mike is the only member of Zapatera to make the merge without sitting out for any challenge. The other four Zapateras who made it to the merge sat out for at least one challenge.
Mike is the highest ranking Zapatera member from Redemption Island.
Mike is the only member of Zapatera to outlast more than two Ometepe members after the merge.

On a blog post, Jeff Probst wonders whether Mike decided to let the 6 players left in the main game at the time spend time with their loved ones instead of having the Redemption Island residents spend time with their loved ones based on genuine kindness or because he thought that would be a good move if he were to make the Final Three. Ultimately, Jeff thinks that it had to do with a little bit of both.
Mike lost 27 lbs. during his time on Redemption Island.
Ashley originally applied for The Amazing Race.
Ashley was the only person voted out on her season to not be sent to Redemption Island.
Ashley was the only female to win more than one individual Immunity Challenge in Redemption Island.
Ashley lost 20 lbs. (9 kg) during Redemption Island.
Semhar was the youngest female member of the Savaii tribe.

In an interview on Rob Has a Podcast, Semhar claimed that during the Immunity Challenge in "I Need Redemption", Jim Rice was initially tapped to be one of Savaii's three shooters, but stepped down. Since nobody would want to take the role as third shooter, Semhar nominated herself instead.
In an interview with TV Guide, Semhar revealed that the location of Redemption Island was at the other end of an island where the Savaii tribe camp was situated.
Mark was the only male contestant of Survivor: South Pacific to not make the merge.
In an interview, Papa Bear revealed that he actually found the hidden clue to the Hidden Immunity Idol, a scene that was not seen, nor explored in the actual episode.
Mark was the oldest member of Savaii.
Jeff Probst actually predicted that Stacey would be one of the first to go, because of her bossy attitude.
Stacey is the oldest woman in South Pacific.
Stacey is the second mortician to participate on Survivor, after Darrah Johnson.
Stacey received votes at both at her Tribal Councils. Also, the person she voted against voted against her.
Stacey has the most votes against her out of any other pre-merge boot in South Pacific, with 10 votes.
Elyse was Miss Washington 2007 and the 2nd Runner-up at Miss America 2008.
Elyse is part American Indian (Yakama), German, Japanese, and Latina.
Keith is the first contestant with a pacemaker.
Keith lost 16 lbs. during his time on South Pacific.

Whitney is the first first-time contestant to compete in another reality show before her run on Survivor. She was a contestant on the 5th season of Nashville Star, and finished in 5th place. She would later be followed by Hayden Moss, who won Big Brother 12 prior to competing on Survivor: Blood vs. Water, the Anderson Twins, who competed on two seasons of The Amazing Race before competing on Survivor: San Juan del Sur, and Caleb Reynolds who competed on Big Brother 16 before competing on Survivor: Kaôh Rōng.
Whitney shares exactly the same birthday as Amanda Kimmel from Survivor: China, Survivor: Micronesia, and Survivor: Heroes vs. Villains.
Whitney and Dawn Meehan were initially supposed to be on Survivor: Nicaragua.
Whitney lost 10 lbs. during her time on South Pacific.
Edna originally intended to talk to Mark Burnett to be on Shark Tank to promote a new business. However, he convinced her to be on Survivor instead.

Edna is a close friend of Survivor: Samoa contestant Mick Trimming, who is also a doctor.
Mick helped her get cast for the show.
Edna was the only Upolu member to receive a vote against her at every pre-merge Tribal Council her tribe attended.

With 15 votes against her, Edna outdid Jerri Manthey and Lindsey Richter's record of 12 votes in a single season against a woman. This was broken in Blood vs. Water by Laura Morett with 19 votes against her.
Edna often wore Tree Mail messages as visors during the game.
Edna lost 14 lbs. during her time on South Pacific.
Rick was the oldest contestant on Survivor: South Pacific.
Rick had applied 14 times before getting cast on South Pacific.
He is the second person to win the Sears competition for a chance to be a Survivor contestant, the first being Survivor: Nicaragua 's Jimmy Tarantino.
Rick is the only person voted out from South Pacific that wasn't sent to Redemption Island, as Ozzy was sent voted out twice before and returned.
Rick lost 23 lbs. during his time on South Pacific.
Albert and Natalie Tenerelli are the only contestants to receive only one vote against them during the game but receive no jury votes and place third.
Rick Nelson gave him the nickname "Prince Albert."
He also shares a hometown with David Samson.
Sophie revealed during the season premiere that she knows Russian and is also an Economics major.
Her father is journalist Thurston Clarke.
Sophie was the youngest female castaway on Survivor: South Pacific.
Sophie is the second first-time player to defeat a returning player at the Final Tribal Council, following Danni Boatwright in Survivor: Guatemala.
Sophie is one of three Sole Survivors, and the most recent one, to receive a vote against them at the first Tribal Council they attended following Jenna Morasca and Chris Daugherty.
Sophie won the most individual Immunity Challenges in South Pacific, with three wins.

On Day 27 of South Pacific, Sophie became the first contestant to win two Immunity Challenges in one day.
Sophie was the only contestant on South Pacific to win consecutive challenges, excluding duels.

Kourtney is the first and currently only female to be medically evacuated from the game.
Kourtney is also tied with Pat Cusack for being the earliest evacuation from the game, both having been evacuated on Day 3.

Kourtney is one of six contestants to never visit Tribal Council. The others are Jonathan Libby, Wanda Shirk, Gary Stritesky, Dana Lambert, and Pat Cusack.
Kourtney, Jonathan, Wanda, and Pat are the only contestants to be eliminated from the game in the first episode by means other than a vote.
Kourtney is the only person on One World to never receive a vote.
Nina was the oldest female castaway on One World and second oldest overall behind Tarzan Smith.

Nina is the second castaway to be the first voted out while not being the first to be eliminated from the game (following Jolanda Jones in Palau), due to Kourtney Moon's medical evacuation. She would be followed by Laura Boneham in Blood vs. Water and Jessica Peet in David vs. Goliath.
Nina is the only castaway to be voted out of the Salani tribe.

Nina was the first player to be eliminated on Day 5.
She is also the first person to be the first one voted out and last longer than three days without going to Redemption Island or becoming part of the Outcasts twist.
Nina is the first player to be the first person voted out of a season and not be voted out in the first episode. She would be followed by Jessica Peet.
Nina is the only person to be voted out first and place 17th.

Bill is the second player to be voted out after a tribe gave up immunity to the opposing tribe following Liliana Gomez from Survivor: Fiji. In the case of Liliana, however, the tribe had to choose whether to keep their camp or keep immunity, in Bill's case, the tribe decided to give up immunity just so they could vote him off.
Coincidently, both contestants placed 15th in their respective seasons.

Colton's fury over Bill attributed from Bill throwing Colton's Hidden Immunity Idol into the ocean. This would be a direct violation of Survivor rules, as Hidden Immunity Idols are considered to be personal items, and thus cannot be stolen. Leif told Colton about the incident, while production returned Colton's idol to him.

Jonas is the fourth male contestant to be the first member of the jury in a Battle of the Sexes season. This means that every Battle of the Sexes season so far has had a male contestant as the first member of the jury (following Dave Johnson, Lea Masters, and Austin Carty).
As Jonas was voted out on Day 20, he held the record for fewest days played among contestants to make both the merge and the jury, until RC Saint-Amour surpassed it the following season.
Jonas lost 12 lbs. during his time in One World.
Jonas was a friend of Jennifer Lanzetti before she competed on Survivor: Kaôh Rōng.
Michael lost 13.8 lbs. during his time in One World.

According to fellow One World castaway Colton Cumbie's exit interview with Reality TV Magazine, Jay was intended to be the recipient of Colton's Hidden Immunity Idol during his medical evacuation. But due to Jay now being a Salani member and Colton's worry of possibly ruining Jay's strategy, Colton decided to keep the idol for himself.
Jay lost 30 lbs. during his time in One World.
Leif is the first "little person" (a person with dwarfism) to play Survivor.
During his time on Survivor: One World, Leif slept in the box that Manono received during the episode 2 Do-It-Yourself Reward Challenge.

Leif and Troyzan Robertson were the only two people to vote against Kim Spradlin.
Furthermore, they were the only two jury members to not vote for her at the Final Tribal Council.
Leif lost 13.3 lbs. during his time in One World.
Tarzan was the oldest contestant on Survivor: One World.
Tarzan prefers to go by "Tarzan", almost similar to tribemate Troy "Troyzan" Robertson.
Jeff Probst claimed that Tarzan had an ego problem, even going as far as telling the medical team how to give a physical examination.
On two occasions, Tarzan wore women's clothing, first was Monica Culpepper's shirt, then Kat Edorsson's top and underwear, both items left at camp before they got eliminated from the game.
Every time Tarzan received a vote, Christina Cha was one of them.
Tarzan had the most votes cast against him in One World with 12 votes.
Tarzan only received votes from females.
Tarzan lost 24.4 lbs. during his time in Survivor: One World.
Alicia's name is pronounced "A-lee-see-uh" (the way it is pronounced in Spanish).
In a confessional featured in "Thanks for the Souvenir", fellow castaway Kat Edorsson stated that she had a dream in which Alicia had killed her in a shopping mall.
Alicia lost 15 lbs. during her time in One World.

It initially appeared that Christina left her money unused at the Survivor Auction, however, in a Twitter announcement, Christina revealed that she actually purchased lasagna for $80 but it was not shown on television, hence why she could not outbid Troyzan by then.
Christina had the most votes cast out of any other female in One World, with 9 votes.
Christina lost 23 lbs. during her time in One World.
Chelsea decided to audition for Survivor with the help of her close friend and Survivor: China contestant Jaime Dugan.
Kim revealed in "Thanks for the Souvenir" that she had her appendix removed.
Kim is tied with Kelly Wiglesworth, Jenna Morasca, and Chrissy Hofbeck for the most individual immunity wins out of any female contestant in a single season, with 4.

Kim is the first female and fourth overall contestant to possess a Hidden Immunity Idol, not use it, and make it to Day 39, following Yul Kwon, Russell Hantz, and Coach Wade. She was followed by Tony Vlachos.
Kim is the second winner to never use their idol, following Yul from Survivor: Cook Islands.
Kim is tied with Natalie White and Sarah Lacina for the most votes for a woman to win a season, with 7.
Kim is the first winner to find a Hidden Immunity Idol without a clue.
In an interview, Kim revealed she gave her unused Hidden Immunity Idol to Troyzan. Troyzan would later sell the idol on eBay and the buyer returned the idol to Kim.

Kim is the fourth Sole Survivor who also won the Fan Favorite Award, following Bob Crowley from Survivor: Gabon, J.T. Thomas from Survivor: Tocantins, and Rob Mariano from Survivor: Redemption Island. She is also the only female winner to win the award.
Kat Edorsson's luxury item in Survivor: Blood vs. Water was a picture of herself and Kim. Kim also had written a letter to Kat.
From all the players from the first 29 seasons, Survivor Oz ranked Kim as the second best player, behind Sandra Diaz-Twine.
Angie was the youngest contestant in Survivor: Philippines.
Dana is the fifth contestant to never visit Tribal Council, following Wanda Shirk, Jonathan Libby, Gary Stritesky, and Kourtney Moon. She would be followed by Pat Cusack.

Following Dana's elimination, Jeff Probst stated that "technically she did quit" because despite being truly very sick, she would be able to go on further, but the pain would be just too much for her body to stand. He also added that in her place, he'd probably have done the same thing.
Dana is the second contestant to quit the game due to a medical reason. She was preceded by Gary Stritesky in Survivor: Fiji, and followed by Bi Nguyen in Survivor: David vs. Goliath.

Dana is one of three castaways from Survivor: Philippines to not receive a vote. The others are Lisa Whelchel and Michael Skupin.
She is the only one of the three not to reach the Final Tribal Council.
She is the only player of her season not to have her name written down, as the other two received one vote each at the Final Tribal Council.
Jeff Probst claimed that his wife was never jealous of Dawson kissing him. Probst even stated his wife was a "good sport" about it.
Dawson is the second contestant to kiss Probst before leaving Tribal Council, following Jan Gentry from Survivor: Thailand when she was voted out.

Dawson is the first female contestant to go by her last name.
She is one of four contestants overall to go by their last name, preceded by John Cochran, and followed by Kyle Jason and Stephanie Gonzalez.
Katie is the first and so far only contestant from Delaware.
RC was the first female castaway to go by her initials.
RC was the youngest female castaway on Tandang.
RC, along with the rest of the Tandang tribe, became the first through sixth contestants to reach the merge without visiting Tribal Council.
RC added 10 lbs. (4.5 kg) before coming to the Philippines. Once she got her post-game weigh-in, RC discovered she lost 5 lbs. (2.3 kg).

She was the first castaway to make it to the merge stage and only attend one Tribal Council, discounting the Tribal Councils she attended as a jury member. She was followed by Nick Maiorano from Survivor: Kaôh Rōng, Jessica Johnston in Survivor: Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers, and Chris Noble in Survivor: Ghost Island.

She was the first player to be the lowest ranking member of two different tribes as she was the first to be eliminated from original Tandang tribe and the first to be voted out from the Dangrayne tribe. She would be followed by Chris Noble in Survivor: Ghost Island.

RC and her father, Craig Saint-Amour, were supposed to compete on Survivor: Blood vs. Water, but were cut due to her father's hypertension and therefore, could not compete. They were replaced by Candice and John Cody. Immediately following their removal from the cast, the Saint-Amours were flown back to Manila to further check on Craig's health.
According to a post on Jeff Probst's Twitter, RC was asked to return for Survivor: Cambodia, but declined the offer.
Jeff was offered a spot to return for Survivor: Cambodia, but he declined.
Jeff lost 22 lbs. during his time in Survivor: Philippines.
Jeff had the first confessional in Philippines.
Artis has applied for Survivor 12 times.
Prior to applying for the final time for Survivor, Artis was diagnosed with, and overcame, stage 4 Cancer.
Artis was the oldest contestant on Survivor: Philippines.
Artis is the lowest placing male member of Tandang.
Artis, along with the rest of the original Tandang tribe, became the first contestants to reach the merge without visiting Tribal Council.
Artis lost 19.3 lbs. during his time in Philippines.
Pete Yurkowski is the youngest male contestant on Philippines.
Caramoan castaway Eddie Fox and Kaôh Rōng castaway Nick Maiorano were alternatives for Pete.
Pete, along with the rest of the Tandang tribe, became the first contestants to reach the merge without visiting Tribal Council.
Pete lost 20 lbs. during his time in Philippines.
Carter is the first Dangrayne tribe member to be voted out unanimously.
Carter is the only person to ever write Michael Skupin's name on the parchment (in this case, a jury vote for "Skoopin") in either season Michael participated in.
Carter is the highest placing member of the original Kalabaw tribe.
Carter lost 18 lbs. during his time in Philippines.
Lisa was the oldest woman in Survivor: Philippines.

When the Tandang tribe painted their initials on a tree at their camp, Lisa put her initials as "LC", using her married name Lisa Cauble, to hide her identity. This was despite the fact that she had divorced her husband Steven Cauble less than a month before the game began.

Being a fan of The Facts of Life as a young adult, returning castaway Michael Skupin recognized her, but could not call her by her stage name Blair because it would throw her off-guard.
Returning castaway Jonathan Penner also recognized her, and later revealed her identity to everyone at the Final Tribal Council, although he was told of her identity by Denise Stapley.
Lisa, along with the rest of the Tandang tribe, became the first group of contestants to reach the merge without visiting Tribal Council.
Lisa is the first castaway to appear in an interview prior to the airing of their elimination episode. Lisa was on the Jeff Probst Show while Survivor: Philippines was in its midway point.
Lisa is the only castaway among the final seven of Philippines to never win individual immunity.
Lisa is the only castaway ever to reach the Final Tribal Council and have immunity every single Tribal Council pre-merge, and then never receive immunity again post-merge.

Lisa and Skupin are the second pair to tie for second place at the Final Tribal Council after Dreamz Herd and Cassandra Franklin of Survivor: Fiji. They would be followed by Dawn Meehan and Sherri Biethman in Survivor: Caramoan, Carolyn Rivera and Will Sims II in Survivor: Worlds Apart, Tasha Fox and Spencer Bledsoe in Survivor: Cambodia, and Hannah Shapiro and Ken McNickle in Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Unlike Dreamz and Cassandra, Lisa and Skupin never received votes against them, and received votes from the jury.

Lisa is the first person ever to defeat Jeff Probst in a Survivor trivia game on the Jeff Probst Show.
During the game, there was a Facts of Life question that lead to Jeff's loss.
Lisa is the first new player to win the Fan Favorite Award in a season to have returning castaways.
Denise is the only member of Matsing to not receive a vote before the tribe's dissolution.

Denise is the only contestant to reach an official merge without being immune at any point before it.
Stephenie LaGrossa reached the individual stage of Survivor: Palau, but Palau did not have an official merge. Mookie Lee reached the individual stage/merge of Survivor: Fiji, but the Ravu tribe was awarded tribal immunity for the fourth Tribal Council despite losing the Immunity Challenge.

Denise is the only person to attend every Tribal Council as a contestant over the course of a season. She attended all 15 Tribal Councils of Survivor: Philippines, including the Final Tribal Council.
Denise is also the only contestant to witness all eliminations in a single season. In addition to the 15 Tribal Councils, she was also present for Dana Lambert's quit.
However, Denise is not the record holder for the most Tribal Councils attended in a season. Mick Trimming, Natalie White, and Russell Hantz attended 16 Tribal Councils in Survivor: Samoa, including the Final Tribal Council and the Tribal Council held after Russell Swan's evacuation.

Denise successfully voted out all of her original Matsing tribemates during Philippines.
She is the second of three players to vote out every other player on their starting tribe, after John Cochran in South Pacific, and followed by Cydney Gillon in Kaôh Rōng.
Because one of Cochran's tribemates, Ozzy Lusth, returned to the game via Redemption Island, Denise is the first to contribute to the permanent elimination of all her original tribemates by voting them out, and second (following Stephenie in Palau) to contribute to the permanent elimination of all her original tribemates in some manner.
Unlike Cochran and Cydney, Denise did not need any revotes to accomplish this feat; Cochran switched his vote to Keith Tollefson after initially voting for Rick Nelson, and Cydney switched her vote to Darnell Hamilton after initially voting for Alecia Holden.

Denise is the third first-time player to win against a returning player, following Danni Boatwright and Sophie Clarke.
Coincidentally, all three of them are female and received six votes to win.
Denise is the second-oldest winner (behind Bob Crowley) and oldest female winner when crowned Sole Survivor, at 41 years, 11 months, and 15 days old.
Denise is the shortest Sole Survivor, at 5 feet tall.
After meeting him on Tinder, Allie helped Joaquin Souberbielle to get on Survivor.
Hope was Miss Missouri USA 2011 and competed in Miss USA 2011 with Survivor: Philippines castaway Katie Hanson, who represented Delaware.
Hope is the first female castaway to be voted out after a three-way tie.
Hope was the only person voted out of the Gota tribe who was not blindsided.

Hope is the only castaway in Survivor history to last more than one episode and only receive one confessional during the entire season.
Hope also has the lowest average confessionals per episode of any castaway in Survivor history, with an average of only 0.33.
Shamar has the most votes cast against him out of any castaway evacuated, with 8.
Shamar received votes at each Tribal Council he attended.

Shamar is the only person to be evacuated from a Fans vs. Favorites season as a Fan.
Even though Erik was also evacuated in Caramoan (where he was a Favorite), in Survivor: Micronesia, he was a Fan.

Matt is the fourth Survivor contestant from Cincinnati, Ohio, following Lillian Morris from Pearl Islands, Michelle Yi from Fiji, and Marisa Calihan from Samoa.
However, he is the first male contestant from Cincinnati.
Fellow tribemate Reynold Toepfer is also originally from Cincinnati, but he resides in California.

Although seventh eliminated from the game, Matt is the first male from Caramoan to be voted out at the Tribal Council site.
Shamar Thomas was evacuated, and Brandon Hantz was voted out in an impromptu Tribal Council at a challenge site.
Julia was the only female Fan on Caramoan to not have blonde hair.
Julia was the youngest contestant on Survivor: Caramoan.
Michael is the oldest member of the original Gota tribe.

Michael is the only Fan switched to the Bikal tribe to reach the merge. As such, he is the only Fan to be a member of all three tribes in Caramoan.
He shares this distinction with Erik Reichenbach from Survivor: Micronesia, who coincidentally was a Favorite in Caramoan.

Michael is the third person to reach the merge with only one challenge win, following Mookie Lee and Denise Stapley.
