However, Michael unofficially won another challenge via forfeit, and Mookie unofficially won another challenge via the Moto tribe giving up immunity.
On the Survivor After Show, Parvati compared him to Eliza Orlins due to his memorable facial expressions.
Reynold lasted the most days out of any male "Fan" without having a vote count against him with 25 (Laura Alexander's vote was negated by the Hidden Immunity Idol and thus not counted).
Reynold is the only Fan to win an individual challenge in Survivor: Caramoan.
Reynold is the only Fan who got to speak at the Reunion Show.
Reynold is the lowest placing Enil Edam member to win individual immunity.
Reynold is the fastest player to find two Hidden Immunity Idols. He found his first idol on Day 5, followed by his second idol on Day 11.

occupation:
Ice Cream Scooper;
Comic Book Artist

trivia: Eddie is the youngest male on the original Gota tribe.

Eddie is the only member of the Three Amigos alliance to not find a Hidden Immunity Idol.
However, he was given an idol by Malcolm Freberg.

Eddie is the highest placing male Fan of Caramoan.
Eddie is the highest placing male Fan in any Fans vs. Favorites season.

Despite Eddie receiving 16 votes, he never received more than four at any Tribal Council.
With 16 votes cast against him, Eddie has received the fifth-most votes in a single season, behind Phillip Sheppard, Ozzy Lusth, and Baylor Wilson who tie at 17, Jenn Brown with 18, and Laura Morett with 19.
Eddie currently holds the record of most failed elimination votes in a single season, with 9.
Eddie is the most targeted person for a split vote, being targeted five times.
He is the only person to vote against Sherri Biethman on more than one occasion.
In a confessional, Eddie mentioned that he would use the million dollar prize to open up a bar where people could bring their dogs.
Survivor: Kaôh Rōng castaway Nick Maiorano revealed he and Eddie were alternatives for Survivor: Philippines castaway Pete Yurkowski, but were cut and pushed to the Caramoan finals.
Sherri was the oldest female on the Gota tribe and the only female not in her 20's to be on the tribe.
Sherri is the first contestant from Idaho.
In an interview, Sherri said that she named her autistic son Colby, after three-time Survivor contestant Colby Donaldson.
Sherri is the only female Fan to make the merge in Caramoan.
Sherri is the only Fan in Caramoan to receive no votes before the merge, if the vote Reynold Toepfer canceled out with his Hidden Immunity Idol is counted.

Sherri is the highest-ranking Fan in Caramoan.
She is the highest-ranking Fan on any Fans vs. Favorites season.
She is also the only Fan to make it to the Final Tribal Council.
She is one of three Fans to reach the final four, alongside Natalie Bolton and Eddie Fox.

Sherri is the only new player in a season with half of the cast of returnees and half newbies to reach the Final Tribal Council.
She is the also the highest ranking new player in a newbies vs. returnees season, being tied for 2nd place.
Sherri is the only player to have to go up the ladder a second time during the "Smash and Grab" challenge to retrieve her key after missing the first time.
Sherri is the only female in Caramoan to reach the jury stage of the game and not win at least one individual Immunity Challenge.
According to Dawn Meehan in an interview, both her and Sherri's total winnings were $92,500 respectively. Dawn said that this was the result of combining the 2nd and 3rd place winnings.
Rachel is the lowest placing member of Tadhana, placing 18th.
Marissa was the youngest contestant on Blood vs. Water.

Marissa, along with fellow Survivor: Blood vs. Water contestants Ciera Eastin, Vytas Baskauskas, and Katie Collins are the second through fifth people to be a blood relative of a past contestant. The first was Brandon Hantz, being the nephew of Russell Hantz.
Marissa holds the record for the most amount of votes received in the shortest amount of time (10 votes by Day 3).
Marissa is the first person to be voted off in Tribal Council, but not be the first person of the season to be voted off, following one of the season's twists.
Marissa is the only female contestant from Tadhana to survive a Redemption Island duel.
Marissa is the first African-American contestant to survive a duel on Redemption Island.
Marissa and John Cody were the only members of Tadhana to survive more than one Redemption Island duel.
John and wife Candice Cody were a replacement pair for Survivor: Blood vs. Water because RC Saint-Amour's father Craig suffered hypertension the day before filming.

John was the first male castaway to be voted out of Blood vs. Water, despite Rupert Boneham and Colton Cumbie being eliminated before he was voted out of his tribe. This is due to Rupert switching with his wife at Redemption Island and Colton quitting.
John and his wife were the first loved ones to be together in the game after Day Zero; they shared Redemption Island, though, and were never on a tribe with each other.
John is the first and currently the only male contestant to lose the final pre-merge duel on Redemption Island.
John is the first new player in Blood vs. Water, to be eliminated after outlasting his loved one.

John and Marissa Peterson were the only members of Tadhana to survive more than one Redemption Island duel.
John is also the only male contestant on Blood vs. Water to survive more than one Redemption Island duel.
John was the only male contestant to be voted out unanimously on Blood vs. Water.
John is the first male contestant on Blood vs. Water to win a Redemption Island duel.

Laura is the first loved one to appear in a previous season on location before becoming an actual contestant. She was Rupert's loved one at the Loved Ones Challenges of Survivor: All-Stars and Survivor: Heroes vs. Villains.
Katie Collins, who also competed in Survivor: Blood vs. Water, appeared as one of Tina Wesson's loved ones in Survivor: The Australian Outback, but only via webcam.
Laura is the oldest member of Tadhana.
Laura is the first castaway to never compete in a challenge for their original tribe but compete for another tribe, due to her being switched to Galang on Day 1 before a challenge took place.
Laura is the first contestant to switch tribes in a Redemption Island season.
Laura is the only castaway to be voted out and switch places with someone to re-enter the game.
Laura is the only contestant to have been voted off more than once before the merge in a single season.

Laura is the fifth contestant (and second female contestant) to be voted off multiple times in one season. She followed Burton Roberts, Matt Elrod, Andrea Boehlke, and Ozzy Lusth, and preceded Laura Morett and Tina Wesson.
Caleb lost 23 lbs. (10.5 kg) during his time in Survivor: Blood vs. Water.
Katie is the only female in Blood vs. Water to be on every available tribe.

Katie and Laura Boneham are the first people to have appeared on Survivor as a loved one before becoming a castaway themselves.
However, she only appeared via webcam in Survivor: The Australian Outback, while Laura has appeared on location as Rupert Boneham's loved one in Survivor: All-Stars and Survivor: Heroes vs. Villains.
Katie and her mother are the first loved ones to be on a tribe together, as Candice and John Cody only shared Redemption Island with each other.
Katie and Tina are 1 of 3 couples to make the merge with their partners with Aras/Vytas and Ciera/Laura M. being the others.
Katie is the first contestant to be shown on a season prior to competing as she was shown on Survivor: The Australian Outback.

Katie is the first first-time playing female castaway to win an Immunity Challenge in a season with an equal amount of returning players and first-time players.
She would later be followed by fellow tribemate Ciera Eastin.

Katie has only received votes from female players.
No one has ever voted against her twice.
She has never received more than one vote at Tribal Council.

Katie is the second castaway after Paschal English to be eliminated from the tribe by participating in the rock drawing tiebreaker. She would late be followed by Jessica Lewis.
However, due to Redemption Island being active, she was still in the game until the following duel.
Of all the people who made the merge in Blood vs. Water, Katie won the least amount of challenges, with only two while others won at least three or more.
Katie lost 14 lbs. (6.35 kg) during her time in Blood vs. Water.
Katie was the only female to compete on Redemption Island during the merge to not survive a duel.

Hayden is the first male first-time contestant to have appeared on another reality show before Survivor, having competed and ultimately winning Big Brother 12. Hayden is the second overall, following Whitney Duncan (of Survivor: South Pacific) who competed on the 5th season of Nashville Star.
Hayden was the first Big Brother contestant to appear on Survivor, He was followed by Caleb Reynolds in Survivor: Kaôh Rōng.
In Caleb's Big Brother 16 bio, he named Hayden as the former Big Brother player he liked the most.
In Survivor: Blood vs. Water, Hayden went the longest without receiving votes against him.

Hayden is the highest placing male Tadhana member.
He only received votes from Gervase Peterson, Monica Culpepper, and Tyson Apostol, the eventual Final Three of the season.
Hayden lost 22 lbs. during his time in Blood vs. Water.

Hayden placed seventh while his girlfriend was the seventh one out.
Hayden is the only loved one in Blood vs. Water to finish at the same place as their partner did in a previous season.
Hayden had an all-man alliance in Big Brother as well as Survivor. In both instances, he outlasted the other members of his alliance.

occupation: YMCA Basketball Coach; Cigar Lounge Owner

trivia: David is the oldest member of the Luzon tribe.
David is the second Survivor contestant to be affiliated in any way with Major League Baseball, following Jeff Kent from Survivor: Philippines.

The season premiere of Cagayan, in which David was voted out, aired on his 46th birthday.
David is the second contestant to be the first person voted out in a premiere that aired on their birthday, following Ryan Aiken from Survivor: The Amazon.
Garrett is the first male to be targeted during the First Impressions twist.
Garrett is the earliest person to find a Hidden Immunity Idol, finding one on Day 1.
Garrett holds the record for having the earliest elimination while in possession of a Hidden Immunity Idol, voted out on Day 6.

J'Tia is the fourth castaway to receive votes from all of their original tribemates but not be voted out at their first Tribal Council, following Shii Ann Huang, Ashley Massaro, and Gillian Larson.
They were followed by Alecia Holden and Patrick Bolton.

J'Tia was mentioned by Jon Misch during "Method to This Madness" in Survivor: San Juan del Sur: "This is like, seriously, I'm thinking like I'm J'Tia right now. J'Tia poured the rice on the fire, and Jon lost the flint."
Cliff is the oldest male castaway in Cagayan.
Cliff is the third-tallest contestant. Standing at 6'10" (208 cm), just short of Mitchell Olson who is 7 feet (213 cm) tall and Scot Pollard who is 6'11" (210 cm).

Cliff is the first former NBA player to compete on Survivor. He is the eighth former athlete from the major American professional sports leagues (NFL, NBA, MLB, NHL) to compete on Survivor, following Ted Rogers, Jr., Gary Hogeboom, Grant Mattos, Steve Wright, Jeff Kent, and Brad Culpepper.
Cliff is the third consecutive African-American to be eliminated on Cagayan, the first two being Brice Johnston and J'Tia Taylor.
Lindsey is the youngest member of the Aparri tribe.
Lindsey originally applied for The Amazing Race with her fiancé at the time, but applied for Survivor instead without his knowledge.
Over the course of their rivalry, Lindsey nicknamed Trish, "Malnutrisha".
Lindsey is the first castaway to quit immediately following a Tribal Council.
Lindsey is the only contestant in Cagayan who never received a vote against them.
Both times Alexis attended Tribal Council she received votes, and each time one was from Morgan McLeod.
Morgan is the youngest castaway from Survivor: Cagayan.
Morgan was the first member of the Solana tribe to have a confessional.
Morgan lost a total of 11 lbs. (5 kg) while on Cagayan.
Out of the four Tribal Councils Morgan participated in, she only voted with the majority once.

Morgan is the only one voted out during the First Impressions twist on Day 1 who did not go on to outlast their Tribe Leader (in her case, LJ McKanas).
Garrett Adelstein outlasted David Samson, while Trish Hegarty outlasted Sarah Lacina.
LJ was the next to be voted out after her.
Morgan McLeod, Morgan McDevitt, and Morgan Ricke are the only contestants to have the same name as a tribe (Morgan of Survivor: Pearl Islands).
LJ is the oldest member of the Solana tribe.
LJ is the only male to make the merge and not have been an Aparri tribe member at any time .
LJ lost 24 lbs. (10 kg) during his time in Cagayan.

LJ was the last original tribe leader in Cagayan to be voted off and the only one to not be the first person voted off of a tribe.
The first two being David Samson and Sarah Lacina.
LJ won the Ozcar for "Sexiest Male" in 2013/14 over fellow tribe mate Jeremiah Wood.
Jeremiah lost 20.7 lbs. (9.4 kg) during his time in Cagayan.
Jeremiah is the male that received the most votes cast against him in Cagayan, with 9.
Jeremiah won the Ozcar for "Sexiest Male" in 2013/14 over fellow tribemate LJ McKanas.

Jeremiah is one of the seven jurors to cast a vote against all of the finalists in their season.
The other six are Shane Powers, Erik Reichenbach, John Fincher, Brett Clouser, Tasha Fox, and Spencer Bledsoe.

Despite only being 22 years old at the time of filming, Jefra is the oldest female member of Solana. Her female tribemates, Alexis Maxwell and Morgan McLeod, were both 21.
She is the youngest contestant to be the oldest member of a tribe from their gender.
Despite being the oldest female member of the original Solana, she was the youngest member of Solana after the tribe switch.

Jefra is the highest-placing member of the original Solana tribe.
She placed 7th, making her one of the lowest-placing contestants to be the highest-placing member of their original tribe, along with Stephenie LaGrossa.
Jefra is the only woman to make the merge and never be a member of Aparri.
Jefra lost 9 lbs. (4 kg) during her time in Survivor: Cagayan.
Jefra is tied with Jeremiah Wood for most votes cast against her in Cagayan, with 9.
Jefra won the most challenges of any woman in Cagayan.
Both times Jefra received votes,  Spencer Bledsoe and Tasha Fox voted against her.

Trish is the oldest castaway on Cagayan.
Trish was the third castaway who was in their forties to be the oldest castaway of a season. The first two were Sekou Bunch in Cook Islands and Chicken Morris in China. The group was followed by Katrina Radke in Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers and Angela Perkins in Ghost Island.
Trish is the highest placing female member of the Aparri tribe.

Trish was referred to by multiple names by her fellow tribemates, often referencing her thin build:
She was referred to as "Malnutrisha" by Lindsey Ogle.
She retaliated by calling Lindsey, "Ding-A-Ling."
She was later called "Anorexia" by Tony Vlachos.
She was also called "Skeletor" and "Psychobitch" by Kass McQuillen.

Trish is the longest lasting castaway of the three eliminated during the First Impressions twist on Cagayan.
She is also the only one of the three to outlast all Tribe Leaders.
She is also the only one among those eliminated in the First Impressions twist to choose the extra bag of rice instead of a clue to a Hidden Immunity Idol.
In addition, Trish holds the record for the number of days survived on a season by a castaway eliminated during any season featuring the First Impressions twist.
Trish lost 10 lbs. (4.5 kg) during her time in Cagayan.
Trish is the only member of the Cagayan final six not to return for a future season.

Nadiya and her sister Natalie are the first two contestants to first appear on The Amazing Race and then appear on Survivor. They were followed by Mike White in Survivor: David vs. Goliath.
She and Natalie are the third and fourth castaways to compete on another reality show before appearing on Survivor. The first two were Whitney Duncan and Hayden Moss. They were followed by Caleb Reynolds and Mike White.
She is the first person to be eliminated first from both shows.
Nadiya and Natalie are the first pair of sisters, and first pair of twins, to have played Survivor together.

Nadiya and Natalie are the fourth and fifth contestants to have dual citizenship following Aras Baskauskas of Survivor: Panama and Survivor: Blood vs. Water, Todd Herzog of Survivor: China, and Abi-Maria Gomes of Survivor: Philippines.
Nadiya was the only person voted off before the tribe switch who had not visited Exile Island.
Val is the oldest female member of the Coyopa tribe.
Val and Keith Nale are the first people to be sent to Exile Island since Coach Wade in Survivor: Tocantins.

Val is the sixth person to be disqualified from a challenge, following Ken Stafford, Robb Zbacnik, Stephanie Dill, Jed Hildebrand, and Ben Browning. However, among all them, Val is the only one to not have her disqualification televised.

Val, along with Dale Wentworth, are the first castaways to become loved ones in a future season. Conversely, Katie Collins and Laura Boneham first appeared on Survivor as a loved one before becoming castaways themselves in Survivor: Blood vs. Water.
John was the third Major League Baseball personality to compete on Survivor, following Jeff Kent and David Samson.
John lost 19 lbs. (8.5 kg) during his time in San Juan del Sur.
Drew is the youngest member of the Hunahpu tribe.
Drew is allergic to crabs and shellfish and was not able to eat what his tribemates could eat.
Drew lost 23 lbs. (10.4 kg) during his time in San Juan del Sur.
Drew was the only person voted out of Hunahpu.
Dale is the oldest contestant competing on Survivor: San Juan del Sur.
Dale was the only male member of Coyopa to remain on Coyopa at the tribe switch.
Dale and Kelley, are the only two contestants on a Blood vs. Water season, to be a Father/Daughter duo.
Dale and Kelley are the first pair of loved ones to be eliminated from the game in San Juan del Sur and the only pair to be eliminated pre-merge.
According to his interview from Survivor Live, Dale and Kelley originally applied for The Amazing Race, but were asked if they wanted to compete on Survivor instead.

Dale, along with Val Collins, are the first castaways to return for a future season as a loved one. They were followed by Monica Culpepper. Conversely, Laura Boneham and Katie Collins first appeared on Survivor as a loved one before becoming castaways themselves in Survivor: Blood vs. Water.
Julie was the only female to win a Hero Duel on Survivor: San Juan del Sur.
Julie is the first female castaway on Survivor: San Juan del Sur to outlast her male partner. Julie also became the first woman to be eliminated after her partner was eliminated.

Julie is the first person to quit after the merge, but not become a juror. However, Probst confirmed in an interview that even if they did go to Tribal Council, the person voted out still would not have been on the jury.
Julie shares the record with Nick Stanbury from Survivor: Panama for the fewest number of days played among castaways who reached the merge, leaving the game on Day 18.
Josh and Reed applied and were cast individually, without the production knowing they were boyfriends.
Josh lost 17 lbs. (7.7 kg) during San Juan del Sur.
Josh celebrated his 33rd birthday at Ponderosa, which was the day after Reed got voted out.
Josh revealed on his Twitter that he was approached to return for Survivor: Cambodia, but he had to decline because his Broadway contract wouldn't allow him to leave.

Wes was one of three firefighters who competed on San Juan del Sur.
The others were his father, Keith Nale, and Jeremy Collins.
He is the only one to not return for Cambodia.
Wes and his father, Keith, were the only remaining contestants on San Juan del Sur to reach the Tribe Switch as a pair, and not end up on the same tribe.
Wes' 24th birthday was on Day 17 of the game.

Wes is the first castaway to have been voted out as a result of two Hidden Immunity Idols.
With only 2 out of 9 votes, Wes held the record for being voted out by the lowest ratio of total votes cast in Survivor history until Lauren Rimmer broke it.
Wes lost 19 lbs. (8.6 kg) during Survivor: San Juan del Sur.
Wes is the only partner of a returning castaway from San Juan del Sur who competed in Cambodia who was not chosen to be a loved one.
Wes only voted with the majority in the pre-merge phase of the game.
Reed and Josh Canfield applied and were cast individually, without production knowing that they were boyfriends.
Reed was the first person in San Juan del Sur to be voted out unanimously.
Reed lost 17.8 lbs. (8 kg) during San Juan del Sur.
Reed was voted out the night before Josh's 33rd birthday.
Reed is the first contestant to be eliminated from the game on Day 29.

Reed claims that he voted for Jaclyn Schultz to win so that she would get second place over Missy Payne, as he figured Natalie Anderson would win regardless.
A similar situation occurred in the original Blood vs. Water when Vytas Baskauskas voted for Monica Culpepper to ensure that she would get second place over Gervase Peterson.

Alec is the youngest male contestant on Survivor: San Juan del Sur.
Coincidentally, Alec's brother, Drew Christy, is the youngest male member of the Hunahpu tribe.
Alec is the first member of Coyopa to outlast his loved one.
Alec is the highest ranking male of Coyopa.
Alec lost 23 lbs. (10 kg) during his time on San Juan del Sur.
Jon and Jaclyn were going to be on The Amazing Race, but were asked to be on Survivor instead.
Jon and Jaclyn are the only male/female pair to both make it to the merge phase in a Blood vs. Water season.
Jon lost 26 lbs. (11.8 kg) during San Juan del Sur.
Jon is the first player to be eliminated from the game on Day 35.
Jaclyn revealed on her Twitter that Jon missed the call and opportunity to possibly be voted to compete in Survivor: Cambodia.
Baylor was the youngest contestant on Survivor: San Juan del Sur.
Baylor and her mother Missy Payne were the only female-female pair of loved ones on the Huyopa tribe.
Baylor is the only castaway in San Juan del Sur to have been involved with both of the two main alliances, being an affiliate of one and an official member of the other.

Baylor had the most votes against her in San Juan del Sur with 17.
This was the record for the most votes received in a non-Redemption Island season (held outright) and the most votes received by a first-time contestant (tied with Phillip Sheppard) until both records were broken by Jenn Brown in Survivor: Worlds Apart.

Baylor was the only female jury member in Survivor: San Juan del Sur and the only female voted out of Huyopa.
She is the first castaway to be the only representative of a gender on the jury.

Baylor was the first person voted out due to a Hidden Immunity Idol "played by default" at the last Tribal Council at which idols could be played.
Because of this, Baylor holds the record for the latest day to be "idoled out", at Day 37. This was tied by Mike Zahalsky in Survivor: Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Baylor is the second jury member to vote for the second runner-up at any Final Tribal Council in the show's history, following Erik Huffman in Survivor: China.
Baylor placed third in 25 "Biggest New Survivor Villains" on Survivor Oz.
Missy is the oldest female castaway competing on Survivor: San Juan del Sur.
Missy is the only female to be on every tribe in San Juan del Sur.
Missy is the second castaway to opt out of an individual Immunity Challenge without being tempted by food. The first was Phillip Sheppard in Survivor: Caramoan.
Missy and her daughter Baylor have coexisted the longest as a pair out of both Blood vs. Water seasons, at 37 days.
Missy is the first person to sit-out at the Final Immunity Challenge.
Missy and Jaclyn Schultz are the first castaways to make it to Final Tribal Council with loved ones on the jury.

Missy is the second third-place finisher to receive a vote from the jury in the Final Three, following Amanda Kimmel in Survivor: China. The women were followed by Ryan Ulrich in Survivor: Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Every time Missy had her name written down at Tribal Council, it was only written down once.
The crutch that Missy used following her injury was incorporated into the Escameca tribe banner's frame.
Jaclyn is the first contestant to have Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser syndrome.
Jaclyn and Jon Misch are the only co-ed pair to have both members reach the merge in a Blood vs. Water season.
Jaclyn and Jon were going to compete on The Amazing Race, but were asked to be on Survivor instead.
Jaclyn revealed on her Twitter that Jon missed the call and opportunity to possibly be voted to compete in Survivor: Cambodia.
Natalie and her sister Nadiya Anderson are the first castaways to first appear on The Amazing Race before competing on Survivor. They were followed by Mike White.
Natalie and her sister Nadiya are the currently the only pair of sisters to play Survivor.
Natalie is the youngest female member of the Hunahpu tribe.
Natalie is the only one of the Final Three in San Juan del Sur to not receive the jury vote of their loved one. This was because her loved one, Nadiya, was eliminated pre-jury.

Natalie is tied with Michele Fitzgerald for the most challenge wins (tribal and individual) for a female Sole Survivor, with 13. She is also the Sole Survivor with the fourth most challenge wins, only preceded by Bob Crowley (14 wins), Mike Holloway (14 wins), and Tom Westman (17 wins).

Natalie is the fourth consecutive castaway named "Natalie" to reach the final four, after Bolton, White, and Tenerelli, the third consecutive castaway named "Natalie" to reach the Final Tribal Council in a Final Three, after White and Tenerelli, and the second castaway named "Natalie" to be crowned the Sole Survivor, after White.

Natalie became the eighth Sole Survivor to win without a vote cast against her during the whole season, following Tina Wesson, Ethan Zohn, Brian Heidik, Sandra Diaz-Twine (in Survivor: Pearl Islands), Tom Westman, J.T. Thomas, and John Cochran.
Natalie is the first Asian-American woman to win Survivor, and the first Asian-American Sole Survivor since Yul Kwon.
Natalie won the RHAP Fan Favorite Player of the Season award with 49% of the votes.
On February 24, 2015, Natalie was elected Miss Survivor 2015.
Natalie was originally cast in Survivor: Game Changers, but she backed out at the last minute and was replaced by Sierra Dawn Thomas.

Natalie, and her twin sister, Nadiya are the fourth and fifth contestants to have dual citizenship following Aras Baskauskas of Survivor: Panama and Survivor: Blood vs. Water, Todd Herzog of Survivor: China, and Abi-Maria Gomes of Survivor: Philippines.
Natalie is currently the only castaway to win Survivor representing another primary CBS reality TV series.

So initially traveled to Nicaragua with her sister, Doo Kim, for Survivor: San Juan del Sur as the tenth and final pair of castaways. However, her sister failed the final medical tests and they were forced to withdraw, hence San Juan del Sur started with ten men and only eight women.
This made So the second castaway to withdraw after being cast on a season, following Tina Scheer from Survivor: Panama, who was originally cast for Survivor: Guatemala, but backed out due to her son's passing a week before filming.
Nina is the second deaf contestant, following Christy Smith from Survivor: The Amazon. However, unlike Christy, Nina lost her hearing later in life.
Whereas Christy used lip-reading to communicate with others, Nina has cochlear implants.
Nina is the oldest member of the Nagarote tribe.
Lindsey is the youngest female on the original Escameca tribe.
Lindsey is the only person from the original Escameca tribe to be voted out before the merge.
Lindsey correctly predicted, at the start of the game, that her original tribe would produce the Sole Survivor.
Joaquin is the youngest member of the original Masaya tribe, and was the only member who was under the age of 30.
Joaquin was the first castaway to cast a vote in Worlds Apart.
Joaquin failed to vote with the majority both times he went to Tribal Council.
Joaquin was recruited to compete on Survivor and had not watched the show before competing.
Kelly is the oldest woman on the original Escameca.
Kelly was the only member of the original Escameca to be switched to Nagarote at the Tribe Switch.
Kelly is the first person since Corinne Kaplan to be voted out after the merge, but not be a member of the Jury.

Jenn is the youngest castaway on Survivor: Worlds Apart.
Jenn is the youngest woman ever to find a Hidden Immunity Idol.

Jenn had the most votes cast against her in Worlds Apart with 18, seven of which were voided by an idol.
She holds the record for the most votes cast against for a first-time player, and most votes cast against for a contestant voted out only once. Laura Morett received 19 votes in Survivor: Blood vs. Water, but was a second-time player and returned from Redemption Island during that season.
Jenn lost 0.2 lbs. (0.09 kg) during Worlds Apart.

Tyler is the sixth Survivor contestant related to the NFL, following Gary Hogeboom, Jimmy Johnson, Steve Wright, Grant Mattos, and Brad Culpepper, and followed by Alan Ball.
Of these seven, Tyler is the first and only one to play as placekicker.
Of these seven, Tyler is the only one to never have appeared on CBS prior to Survivor, as CBS aired at least one NFL game involving each of the other six.
Tyler is tied with Gary for the second highest finishing placement, with Brad beating them both with his placement in Survivor: Game Changers. However, Tyler and Gary are eclipsed by Grant in terms of days played.
Tyler lost 26 lbs. (11.8 kg) during Worlds Apart.
Tyler is the only person in Worlds Apart to win exactly one individual Immunity Challenge.
Dan is the second castaway from Gorham, Maine, following Julie Berry.
Dan is the oldest member of Escameca and the oldest male of Survivor: Worlds Apart.
Dan is the first castaway to vote twice at a Tribal Council due to an extra vote advantage.
Dan lost 42.4 lbs. during his time on Worlds Apart.
Dan placed first on 25 "New Biggest Survivor Villains" list on Survivor Oz.
Rodney is the youngest member of the original Escameca tribe and the youngest male castaway in Survivor: Worlds Apart.

Rodney holds the Survivor record for the longest period of time without a challenge win of any kind, winning no challenges from Day 15-38 for a 24-day losing streak. Rodney also holds the post-merge record, winning no challenges throughout his 22-day stay on Merica.
Rodney's 25th birthday was on Day 30 in Worlds Apart.
Rodney placed second in 25 "Biggest New Survivor Villains" on Survivor Oz.
Rodney revealed on a Reddit thread that he was recruited to compete on Survivor in Boston.
Rodney lost 33 lbs. during his time in Worlds Apart.
Carolyn is the oldest castaway on Survivor: Worlds Apart at 52 years old.
Carolyn was often referred to as "Mama C" by her fellow castaways during the game.

Carolyn is the only female contestant to win individual immunity in Worlds Apart.
Carolyn is tied with Kristina Kell and Sabrina Thompson for the second earliest discovery of a Hidden Immunity Idol by a woman, finding one on Day 2.

Carolyn is the highest placing member of the Masaya tribe.
Each of the three starting tribes had a representative in the Final Three, with Carolyn representing Masaya (White Collar).
Carolyn was in the running to return for Survivor: Game Changers, but didn't make the cut.
Will was the oldest male on the original Nagarote tribe.
Will's 42nd birthday was on Day 9 of Worlds Apart.
Will was the highest-ranking member of the original Nagarote tribe.
Both times Will attended Tribal Council and received votes against him, he received exactly two.
Darnell is the youngest male contestant on Survivor: Kaôh Rōng.
Darnell is the first African-American male to be eliminated first since Sekou Bunch from Survivor: Cook Islands.
Jennifer is the only castaway to ever stand up on one of the seats at Tribal Council and give a speech.
Jennifer was friends with One World contestant Jonas Otsuji before competing on Kaôh Rōng.
Liz was recruited for the show by Survivor: Tocantins and Survivor: Cambodia contestant Stephen Fishbach, whom she briefly dated.
Liz was the youngest member of the original Chan Loh tribe.
Liz was the only person voted out of the Chan Loh tribe.

Alecia is the fifth castaway to receive votes from all of their original tribemates but not be voted out at their first Tribal Council, following Shii Ann Huang, Ashley Massaro, Gillian Larson, and J'Tia Taylor.
They would be followed by Patrick Bolton.
Alecia is the only castaway with this distinction to survive the Tribal Council at which she achieved this distinction.
In "The Circle of Life", Alecia's luxury item was revealed to be a letter from her father.
Alecia and Aubry Bracco have the record for most votes cast against them in Kaôh Rōng, with 8 each.
Anna was the oldest female member of the original Gondol tribe.

Anna is the only member of the original Gondol tribe to be voted out prior to the merge.
Caleb Reynolds, another original Gondol member, was also eliminated pre-merge, but this was due to a medical evacuation.
Peter had the first confessional of the season in Survivor: Kaôh Rōng.
Peter was the youngest male member of both the original Chan Loh tribe and the post-swap Gondol tribe.
At every Tribal Council Peter attended, there was six castaways who were present and he voted against a woman who cast her vote against him in return.
Peter is the only male member of the original Chan Loh tribe not to be medically evacuated from the game.
Neal has a twin brother, Carl, who happens to be married to another twin, hence their ice cream brand name, Three Twins.

Neal is the second person to be evacuated with a Hidden Immunity Idol in his possession, following Colton Cumbie of Survivor: One World.
Coincidentally, both were the second person evacuated from their respective seasons.

Neal is the fourth person to be evacuated and become a member of the jury, following Bruce Kanegai (Panama), James Clement (Micronesia), and Erik Reichenbach (Caramoan). Unlike the other three, he was removed from the jury before the Final Tribal Council.
Neal lost 17 lbs. during his time in Survivor: Kaôh Rōng.

Because he was removed from the jury, Neal is the first person to reach the jury stage yet not be present at the Final Tribal Council.
Had he been allowed on the jury, Neal claimed he was voting for Aubry Bracco to be the Sole Survivor.
Prior to competing on Survivor, Nick was a blogger on Rob Has a Podcast.
Nick revealed he and Survivor: Caramoan castaway Eddie Fox were alternates for Survivor: Philippines castaway Pete Yurkowski, but were cut and pushed to Caramoan finals.
Nick, along with Michele Fitzgerald and Chris Noble currently hold the record for surviving the most days without attending Tribal Council, at 22 Days.

Nick is the second castaway to reach the merge and only attend one Tribal Council as a contestant, after RC Saint-Amour in Philippines. The two were followed by Jessica Johnston in Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers and Chris Noble in Ghost Island.
Nick is tied with Marcus Lehman for highest placement (10th) without having survived a Tribal Council without immunity.
Nick lost 31 lbs. during his time in Survivor: Kaôh Rōng.
Nick was the only male in the original Gondol tribe to be voted out, as Caleb Reynolds was medically evacuated and Tai Trang was a finalist.
Scot is the second former NBA player to compete on Survivor, following Cliff Robinson in Cagayan.
At 6' 11" (210 cm), Scot is the second-tallest Survivor contestant ever, just short of Mitchell Olson, who is 7 feet (213 cm) tall.
Scot is the oldest member of the To Tang tribe.
Scot lost 46 lbs. during his time on Kaôh Rōng.

Julia is the youngest contestant to compete on Survivor: Kaôh Rōng and the youngest female Survivor contestant at the time of filming.
Julia is the youngest female contestant to win individual immunity.
Julia's 19th birthday occurred on Day 10 of Kaôh Rōng.
Julia currently ties with Tai Trang and Erik Reichenbach in Survivor: Caramoan for the record of the most consecutive Reward Challenges won, either by tribal and/or individual, with 8.
Julia was voted out on Day 29, which was April 27, 2015. Julia's boot episode aired on April 27, 2016, exactly one year later. Julia is the only contestant with this distinction.
Julia only received votes at her first and last Tribal Councils.
Julia lost 11 lbs. during her time on Kaôh Rōng.
In "The Circle of Life", Jason's luxury item was revealed to be a teddy bear.
Jason lost 23 lbs. during his time on Kaôh Rōng.
Joe is the first Survivor contestant in his 70's since Rudy Boesch from Survivor: Borneo and Survivor: All-Stars.

Joe is the highest ranking male member of the original Chan Loh tribe.
At 71 years old at the time of filming, Joe is the oldest person to be the highest-ranking member of a particular gender on any starting tribe.
Joe coined the name of his season's merged tribe.
Joe lost 20 lbs. during his time in Kaôh Rōng.
Joe was the first person eliminated on Day 34.
Joe is the first castaway to be the third medical evacuation in any season.
Cydney is both the youngest and the highest-ranking member of To Tang.
Cydney is the only female member of To Tang to make it to the merge in Survivor: Kaôh Rōng.

Cydney successfully voted out all five of her To Tang tribemates.
She is the third castaway ever to successfully vote out all of her original tribemates during a single season, after John Cochran (in Survivor: South Pacific) and Denise Stapley.
Cydney is the first person to be the last voted out of a season and not be voted out the day before the Final Tribal Council.
Cydney lost 28 lbs. during her time on Kaôh Rōng.

Michele, along with Nick Maiorano and Chris Noble currently hold the record for surviving the most days in the game without attending Tribal Council, with 22.
Of those three, Michele is the only one who was not voted out at their first Tribal Council.
Michele is the first winner to never visit Tribal Council during the pre-merge portion of the game.
Michele only attended 6 regular Tribal Councils, the fewest for any finalist and winner.
Michele is the least vulnerable female winner and the second overall behind Tom Westman, having been eligible to be voted out only 4 times.

Michele was the only person in Survivor: Kaôh Rōng to win more than one Individual Immunity Challenge.
Michele is the second woman who was the only castaway to win multiple Individual Immunity Challenges in a season after Kelly Wiglesworth in Survivor: Borneo.

Michele has secured her seat at the Final Tribal Council earlier than any other contestant - after the Immunity Challenge on Day 37.
Yul Kwon, Aubry Bracco, and Tai Trang have also secured their seats at the Final Tribal Council on Day 37, but only after Tribal Council that night.
Michele is the first contestant to be able to eliminate a juror from the game.
Michele is tied with Natalie Anderson for the most challenges (both tribal and individual) won by a female winner, with 13.
Michele became the third person from New Jersey to win in 5 seasons, following Tony Vlachos and Natalie Anderson.
Rachel previously applied for Survivor: San Juan del Sur along with her father. However, Rachel turned down the offer because her father was unable to compete due to having knee surgery.
Rachel is the first person to be voted off on Day 4, due to the postponing of the first Immunity Challenge because of a tropical cyclone.

Mari is the oldest member of the original Vanua tribe.
She is the only original member of Vanua to be over 30 during the season's filming.
Mari is friends with Erin & Joslyn, who competed on the twenty-eighth season of The Amazing Race.
Mari previously hosted Smosh Pit Weekly and Smosh Games for the popular YouTube channel Smosh.
Paul is the oldest castaway to compete on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Paul is the only male castaway to be eliminated pre-merge in Millennials vs. Gen X.
Lucy is one of four players to be voted out by only two votes against them before the merge, the others being Ibrehem Rahman, Russell Swan (in Philippines), and Alan Ball.
Lucy is the third player to be voted out as a result of a Hidden Immunity Idol being played before the merge, after Cirie Fields and Tyson Apostol (both in Heroes vs. Villains).
CeCe had previously applied 15 times before being cast on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X, and had been applying since Survivor: The Australian Outback.
CeCe received votes at every Tribal Council she attended.
Out of CeCe's 9 original tribemates, only Ken McNickle and Rachel Ako never voted against her at Tribal Council.
Figgy is the youngest woman to compete on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.

Figgy received exactly three votes at both of the Tribal Councils she attended: one from Adam Klein, one from another man, and one from a woman, also receiving the vote of the contestant she voted for.
Michelle is the first castaway to be voted out on Day 23.
Michelle lost 12 lbs. after competing on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Taylor had the first confessional of Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Taylor is the lowest placing male member of the original Vanua tribe.
Taylor lost 15 lbs. after competing on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.

Taylor is the only contestant from Idaho to not make Final Tribal Council.
Sherri Biethman was the joint Runner Up in Survivor: Caramoan, and Ben Driebergen won Survivor: Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Hammons is the second contestant from Oklahoma, the first being Scout Cloud Lee from Survivor: Vanuatu.
Chris lost 33 lbs. during his time on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Jessica is the first castaway to find a Legacy Advantage.
Jessica is the third person to be eliminated via a rock draw, following Paschal English and Katie Collins.
Jessica lost 13 lbs. during her time on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Both times she received votes at Tribal Council, Bret LaBelle, Chris Hammons, and Sunday Burquest were one of them.
Will is the youngest Survivor contestant at the time of filming, being 18 during Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Will is the first Survivor contestant to be a high-school student at the time of filming.
Will is the first male contestant to win the When It Rains, It Pours challenge.
Will is the youngest person to win an individual Immunity Challenge.
Will lasted the longest without receiving a vote against him in Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Will lost 20 lbs. during his time on Millennials vs. Gen X.
Sunday is the oldest woman to compete on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Sunday is the highest ranking female member of the original Takali tribe.
Sunday lost 25 lbs. during her time on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Sunday only received votes at her first and last Tribal Councils.

Jay was the first castaway in Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X to play a Hidden Immunity Idol for himself. He would be followed by Adam Klein.
Both of them failed to negate the majority of the votes cast against them.
Jay lost 12 lbs. during his time on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Jay was initially cast as an alternate for Survivor: Kaôh Rōng prior to making it on to the cast of Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Jay is the third contestant of Peruvian descent, following Cecilia Mansilla and Kel Gleason.
Bret lost 36 lbs. during his time on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
In 2014, Bret appeared as a guest on 12th season of Top Chef.
David lost 10 lbs. during his time on Millennials vs. Gen X.
David voted correctly at every Tribal Council he attended except for during the rock draw tiebreaker on Day 30, in which he had no vote, and his own elimination.
Hannah took a Survivor college class taught by Max Dawson.
Hannah is the highest ranking female to compete on Survivor: Millennials vs. Gen X.
Hannah is the highest ranking member of the Ikabula tribe.
Hannah placed 14th in TV Guide's "20 Best Performances of 2016".

Ken ties with Denise Stapley, Mick Trimming, Natalie White, Russell Hantz (in Samoa), and Spencer Bledsoe (in Cambodia) for the most Tribal Councils attended in a season, with 15 (including the Final Tribal Council).
Ken is the youngest member of the original Takali tribe.
Ken is the highest placing member of Takali.
Ken is the first person to use the Legacy Advantage.
Ken is the first person from an "older" tribe to reach the Final Tribal Council.
Adam was the one who suggested the name Vinaka for the merged tribe.
Adam is the first castaway to find and possess the Reward Steal advantage.
Adam set the record for the latest discovery of a Hidden Immunity Idol, finding his second one on Day 37. Ben Driebergen tied this record in Survivor: Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Adam is currently the youngest winner by date of birth.

Adam is the fifth person to win Survivor in a unanimous vote, following Earl Cole, J.T. Thomas, John Cochran, and Jeremy Collins.
Adam is tied with Jeremy for the most jury votes in a single season, with ten.
Adam has the most total votes against him for a unanimous winner, with six.
Adam is the second Sole Survivor to take part in a rock draw tiebreaker, after Tyson Apostol.
Katrina is the oldest contestant to compete on Survivor: Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.

Patrick is the oldest male member of the Yawa tribe.
Being 24 at the time of filming, Patrick is the youngest male to be the oldest male of a tribe and only second to Jefra Bland, in terms of being the youngest person to be the oldest member of their tribe by gender.
Patrick and fellow Yawa tribemate Ali Elliott were neighbors and attended the same college, Auburn University, before the game.

Patrick is the sixth castaway to receive votes from all of their original tribemates but not be voted out at their first Tribal Council, following Shii Ann Huang, Ashley Massaro, Gillian Larson, J'Tia Taylor, and Alecia Holden.
Patrick is the only male contestant to hold this distinction.

Alan is the seventh person in the history of the show who was affiliated with the NFL (sixth as a former player) before competing on Survivor, following Gary Hogeboom, Jimmy Johnson, Grant Mattos, Steve Wright, Brad Culpepper, and Tyler Fredrickson.
Roark was the only member of Soko that did not make the merge.
In Survivor: Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers, Ali was the only person who switched tribes and was voted out pre-merge.
Ali and fellow Yawa tribemate Patrick Bolton were neighbors and attended the same college, Auburn University, before the game.
Ali currently works as a personal assistant for YouTube personality, GloZell Green.

Jessica, along with Cole Medders and Mike Zahalsky, are the first contestants to win every challenge pre-merge.
Jessica, Cole, and Mike also tied with Randy Bailey in Gabon for the most consecutive challenge wins, with 10.
Jessica is the only female on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers to make the merge and not win individual immunity.

Jessica is the third castaway to make the merge and be voted out at the first Tribal Council they attended, following RC Saint-Amour and Nick Maiorano. They were followed by Chris Noble.
However, unlike the other three, Jessica was not included as a member of the jury.
Desi was crowned Miss Virginia 2013 and then went on to win Miss Virginia USA in 2016.

Desi is the first African–American contestant to win the first post-merge individual Immunity Challenge of any season.
Jolanda Jones in Palau and G.C. Brown in Gabon also won the first individual Immunity Challenge of their respective seasons, though these challenges were held pre-merge.
Desi is the highest placing female member of the original Soko tribe.
Desi lost 7 lbs. during her time on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Cole is the youngest member of the original Soko tribe.

Cole, along with Jessica Johnston and Mike Zahalsky, are the first contestants to win every challenge pre-merge.
Cole, Jessica, and Mike are also tied with Randy Bailey in Gabon for the most consecutive challenge wins, with 10.

Cole is the only male to win Individual Immunity in Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers. Cole is the only the second male who was the only male to win Individual Immunity during a season, following Robert DeCanio in Marquesas.
Cole lost 13.5 lbs. during his time on Heroes vs. Healers. vs. Hustlers.
JP lost 22 lbs. during his time on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Joe received the most votes out of anyone in Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers, with 12.
Joe lost 20 lbs. during his time on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Lauren is the oldest member of the original Yawa tribe.
Lauren is the highest placing female member of the original Yawa tribe.

Lauren is the first castaway to be eliminated by a single vote, excluding 1-0 votes at a three-person Day 38 Tribal Council.
Receiving only 1 out of 7 votes, Lauren was voted out by the smallest ratio of votes in Survivor history.
Lauren is the first castaway to possess the Extra Vote and be eliminated without using it.
Lauren is one of three contestants to possess both a Hidden Immunity Idol and an advantage at the same time, along with Tai Trang and Adam Klein.
Lauren lost 19 lbs. during her time on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Ashley is the youngest member of the original Levu tribe.
Ashley appeared as an extra in the 2017 film Baywatch. Coincidentally, Nicaragua and Caramoan castaway Brenda Lowe appeared in the film as well.
Ashley lost 16 lbs. during her time on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Mike is the oldest member of the original Soko tribe and the oldest male to compete on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.

Mike, along with Cole Medders and Jessica Johnston, are the first contestants to win every pre-merge challenge.
Mike, Cole, and Jessica also tied with Randy Bailey in Gabon for the most consecutive challenge wins, with 10.
Mike is the highest-ranking member of the original Soko tribe.
Mike lost 17 lbs. during his time on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Mike is tied with Baylor Wilson for latest day being idoled out, both being idoled out on day 37
Devon was the youngest contestant on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Devon lasted the longest without receiving an elimination vote against him in Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Devon lost 19 lbs. during his time on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Ryan is highest-ranking member of the original Yawa tribe.

Ryan is the third castaway to received a jury vote and finish in third place, following Amanda Kimmel in China and Missy Payne in San Juan del Sur.
Ryan is the first male to achieve this feat.

There were numerous revisions on Chrissy's CBS bio, such as stating that her occupation is a financial analyst and that the past Survivor contestant she is most like was Jenna Morasca. While some changes, such as her occupation and hometown were likely corrections, her other changed answers, such as her answer to the Survivor contestant she is most like, were changed for unknown reasons.
Chrissy had the first confessional of Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.
Chrissy is the first female to have obtained a super idol.
Chrissy is the highest ranking female on Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers.

Chrissy is the fourth female to win four individual Immunity Challenges in a season, following Kelly Wiglesworth in Borneo, Jenna Morasca in The Amazon, and Kim Spradlin in One World.
Chrissy is the seventh female to win the four individual Immunity Challenges overall following Kelly, Jenna, Amanda Kimmel, Parvati Shallow, Kim, and Andrea Boehlke.
Chrissy is the oldest female to achieve this feat.

Chrissy is the third castaway to finish in second place outright in a Final Three where all finalists received jury votes. The first two were Courtney Yates in China and Jaclyn Schultz in San Juan del Sur.
Like Courtney and Jaclyn, Chrissy also received two jury votes.
Ben is the third castaway from Idaho, the first two being Sherri Biethman and Taylor Stocker.
Ben is the oldest and highest placing male member of the original Levu tribe.

Ben is the first person to negate every single vote but his own with a Hidden Immunity Idol.
Ben holds the record for the highest percentage of votes negated with the Hidden Immunity Idol at roughly 85.71%.
Ben is tied with Russell Hantz in Samoa, Tony Vlachos in Cagayan, and Tai Trang in Game Changers for the record for the most Hidden Immunity Idols found in a season, with 3.
Ben is the first castaway to play an idol at three consecutive Tribal Councils.
Ben is the first person to play an idol before the votes were cast under the current rules.
Ben has the shortest time between playing an idol and finding another one, finding his third idol the in the same night he played the second idol.

Ben holds the record for the most votes cast against a Sole Survivor, receiving 11 votes in Heroes vs. Healers vs. Hustlers. This record was previously held by Panama winner Aras Baskauskas, who received 9 votes in his season.
Of all Sole Survivors, Ben played the most imperfect game, receiving 11 votes against him and losing 3 jury votes, totaling up to 14 votes lost.
Ben is the second castaway to become the Sole Survivor and win a fire-making challenge, following Bob Crowley. They were followed by Wendell Holland.
Jacob is the first castaway to be sent to Ghost Island.
Morgan lost 7 lbs. during her time on Ghost Island.
Brendan is the oldest male contestant competing on Ghost Island.

For personal reasons, Stephanie was absent from the Ghost Island reunion.
She is the fourth castaway to not attend a Reunion Show, after Brandon Hantz, Brenda Lowe, and Vytas Baskauskas.
She is the first new player with this distinction.
According to Jeff Probst, James has the highest IQ of any Survivor contestant.
Chris is the first person to not attend a pre-merge Tribal Council without winning every tribal Immunity Challenge.

Chris is the first person to be voted out without ever casting a vote.
He is also the first person whose first and only vote cast is as part of the jury at the Final Tribal Council.
Chris is tied with Michele Fitzgerald and Nick Maiorano for lasting the most days without visiting Tribal Council at 22 days.

Chris is the second castaway, following RC Saint-Amour in Philippines, to be the lowest ranking member of two different tribes. In his case, Chris is the lowest ranking member of the Yanuya and Lavita tribes.
Chris lost 12 lbs. during his time on Ghost Island.
Libby lost 13 lbs. during her time on Survivor: Ghost Island.
Desiree is the youngest female contestant on Survivor: Ghost Island.
Desiree lost 12 lbs. during her time on Ghost Island.
Jenna lost 10 lbs. during her time on Ghost Island.

Michael received the most votes out of anyone in Ghost Island, with 15.
Michael lost 21 lbs. during his time on Ghost Island.
Chelsea lost 8 lbs. during her time on Ghost Island.

Kellyn is the first female to be sent to Ghost Island.
Kellyn is the first contestant to decline a game at Ghost Island.
Kellyn is also the first person to be sent to Ghost Island twice.
Kellyn lost 16 lbs. during her time on Ghost Island.

Sebastian and Laurel Johnson are the first contestants to be on three tribes before the merge on their first season.
They are the sixth and seventh overall following Jenna Lewis, Jerri Manthey, and Rupert Boneham on Survivor: All-Stars, Andrew Savage on Survivor: Cambodia, and Cirie Fields on Survivor: Game Changers.
Sebastian lost 6 lbs. during his time on Survivor: Ghost Island.
Donathan lost 15 lbs. during his time on Ghost Island.

Angela is the oldest contestant to compete on Ghost Island.
Being 42 at the time of filming, Angela is the youngest castaway who was the oldest contestant of a season.
Angela is the only person without individual immunity to receive no votes at the Double Elimination twist in Ghost Island.

Laurel and Sebastian Noel are the first contestants to be on three tribes before the merge on their first season.
They are the sixth and seventh overall following Jenna Lewis, Jerri Manthey, and Rupert Boneham in All-Stars, Andrew Savage in Cambodia, and Cirie Fields in Game Changers.

Laurel is the first castaway to cast a tiebreaker vote at the Final Tribal Council.
Due to the tie vote, Laurel is the first castaway since Elisabeth Filarski in The Australian Outback to become a juror on Day 39.
Laurel is the first and only person to be the 11th member of the jury.
Domenick is the first person to simultaneously hold the Legacy Advantage and a Hidden Immunity Idol.
Domenick is the first person to use the Legacy Advantage before the final six.
Domenick was the last person to receive their first vote in Ghost Island.
Domenick received the most jury votes of any runner-up, with 5.
Wendell is the first castaway to win after a tie vote at the Final Tribal Council.
Wendell is the first male, and second castaway overall, to be on an auxiliary tribe and become the Sole Survivor.

Wendell is the second castaway to be the highest placing member in three different tribes, after Sarah Lacina.
He is the first male with this distinction.
Pat is tied with Kourtney Moon for the earliest medical evacuation, being pulled from the game on Day 3.
Pat is one of six contestants to never visit Tribal Council. The others are Jonathan Libby, Wanda Shirk, Gary Stritesky, Kourtney Moon, and Dana Lambert.
Pat is the only male David member who did not make the merge.

Jessica is the youngest contestant to compete on David vs. Goliath.
Jessica is currently the youngest Survivor contestant by date of birth.
Being 19 at the time of filming, Jessica is the youngest person to be the first person voted out of Survivor.
Jessica currently holds the record for the latest first person voted out, being voted out on Day 6.

Jeremy is the only male in David vs. Goliath to get voted out pre-merge, as Pat Cusack was evacuated.
Furthermore, he is the only male Goliath who got voted out pre-merge.
Bi is the third contestant to quit the game due to a medical reason. She was preceded by Gary Stritesky in Survivor: Fiji, and Dana Lambert in Survivor: Philippines.
Natalia is the second castaway of Muslim faith, following Ibrehem Rahman and the first woman to be so.
Natalie is the oldest contestant to compete on David vs. Goliath.
Lyrsa received votes at every Tribal Council she attended.
Elizabeth is the first person to be unanimously voted out of the first Tribal Council of a merged tribe.
Elizabeth currently holds the record for most votes received, excluding revotes, at a single Tribal Council, with 12.
Elizabeth lost 9 lbs. during her time on David vs. Goliath.

Survivor marks John's second appearance on reality television following his first appearance on Tough Enough III, where he and the late Matt Capotelli both won that season, in addition to a WWE contract.
John lost 11 lbs. during his time on David vs. Goliath.
Dan is the first person to play a Hidden Immunity Idol, then also have its effects negated by an Idol Nullifier.
Dan lost 26 lbs. during his time on David vs. Goliath.
Alec is the youngest male contestant to compete on Survivor: David vs. Goliath and also the youngest member of the original Goliath tribe.
Alec is the third contestant to be banned from attending the Reunion Show, following Brandon Hantz and Vytas Baskauskas.
Alec lost 9 lbs. during his time on David vs. Goliath.
Carl is the oldest member of the original David tribe.
Carl is the first castaway to find an Idol Nullifier. Subsequently, He is also the first castaway to use the Idol Nullifier to void another player's Hidden Immunity Idol.
Carl lost 10 lbs. during his time on Survivor: David vs. Goliath.
Gabby is the highest-ranking female member of the original David tribe.
Gabby lost 13 lbs. during her time on David vs. Goliath.

Davie was not part of the originally intended cast for Survivor: David vs. Goliath, as he was initially meant to appear on the 38th season of Survivor instead. He was called at the last minute as a replacement for one of the original contestants of David vs. Goliath, who dropped out for unrevealed reasons.

Mike previously competed with his father, Mel, on two seasons of another CBS primetime reality television series, The Amazing Race.
Mike is the third former The Amazing Race contestant to cross over to Survivor, following Nadiya and Natalie Anderson, who competed in Survivor: San Juan del Sur.
Mike is the oldest male to compete on Survivor: David vs. Goliath.
Jeff Probst stated that it was Mike who discouraged him from bringing back Redemption Island for Survivor: San Juan del Sur.
Mike is the highest-ranking male member of the original Goliath tribe.
